		<item>
		<title>Community Service</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/z6shZWG050M/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/29/community-service/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 Jan 2012 04:32:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1957</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[There&#8217;s this lady in my neighborhood. She started out pleasant enough, but I&#8217;ve since found her to be judgmental, fickle, overbearing, pushy, and loud. I&#8217;m not talking about me just yet. I&#8217;m talking about Sharon, the red headed sixty-something who chain smokes, suns her wig outdoors, and has a country twang that could hail from [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/SmallPlantCutting.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1958" title="SmallPlantCutting, www.honeyehlpyourself.com" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/SmallPlantCutting.jpg" alt="" width="284" height="423" /></a></p>
<p>There&#8217;s this lady in my neighborhood. She started out pleasant enough, but I&#8217;ve since found her to be judgmental, fickle, overbearing, pushy, and loud. I&#8217;m not talking about me just yet. I&#8217;m talking about Sharon, the red headed sixty-something who chain smokes, suns her wig outdoors, and has a country twang that could hail from just about any notch on the Bible belt.</p>
<p><span id="more-1957"></span></p>
<p>Sharon is the eyes and nose of our neighborhood, and she has confirmed that she&#8217;s aware of what I&#8217;m doing, how I&#8217;m doing, where I&#8217;m doing it, and who I&#8217;m doing it with. My second floor bedroom window looks across the parking lot and faces her apartment. Sharon lives right across from me, which means I shouldn&#8217;t have been surprised back in August when she responded to my indoor gardening question by commenting on how much I left my windows open and the rate at which I came and went in my <em>cute little car that I bet must have cost a right pretty penny. Now what is it you </em>do<em> again, sweetheart?</em></p>
<p>One day I stopped in to her place because she wanted to give me a houseplant. She and I share a love of plants, and when she offered to give me one, I was happy to accept. When she handed me the old jelly jar with the cutting in it, I noticed the half empty vodka bottles on the counter. They were party-sized and they suddenly seemed to explain everything: why she talked a little loud sometimes and didn&#8217;t seem to be aware of it, why she set her bright red wig outside on her &#8216;beauty stand&#8217; whenever the weather was good and she wasn&#8217;t wearing it and why she couldn&#8217;t ever seem to hold the thread of a full conversation.</p>
<p>There was that time I invited her over to diagnose my sick ficus tree. I&#8217;d been struggling with it, trying every remedy I could think of, and if anybody knew what to do about it, it was Sharon. She had dozens in her apartment and as many crowding the patio table where she kept her wig and ashtray. It was probably four days out of seven that I&#8217;d seen her out front spraying her hanging plants, careful not to douse the burning end of her cigarette.</p>
<p>Sharon examined my my ailing plant with the attention of a doting mother to a feverish child. She suggested I follow her lead and fill a bottle with soapy water and spray the leaves. <em>That&#8217;ll kill any of them little $#%^! bugs on &#8216;em, darlin.</em> I asked her to repeat herself because I&#8217;d been so stunned at hearing her the first time around. Instead of referring to the pests as mealy bugs, Sharon used a gay slur and didn&#8217;t waste any time repeating it. I shot her a look. <em>Oh,</em> she said, waving me off, <em>my daughter tells me I all the time, she says, &#8216;Mama you shouldn&#8217;t be calling them bugs that,&#8217;</em> Sharon shrugged her shoulders. <em>I know, but that&#8217;s just what I always called em.</em></p>
<p>I didn&#8217;t challenge Sharon on her language because I knew there was a whole lot more where that came from, and all I wanted was plant advice. Remember back when I said I was going to invite Boulder folks to my place for a <a title="Nuts ‘n’ Honey" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/06/19/nuts-n-honey/">cultural sensitivity meet-n-greet</a>? Let&#8217;s just say Sharon is on my list. When I turned toward the door to in an attempt to close our visit, Sharon turned toward me and asked if I was single. I told her I was. <em>So you&#8217;re in the market, sweetheart?</em> I nodded, adding that I hadn&#8217;t actively been seeking anybody but, yes, I nodded. I was available.</p>
<p>Sharon gave me the fish-eyed once over, no doubt sizing up my suitability for potential matches. I knew that look. She leaned in, placed her hand on my forearm and pressed, <em>&#8230;. for a man?</em> Yes I said. <em>Have you met Phil?</em> she asked.</p>
<p>According to Sharon, Phil was <em>more horizontal than vertical if you don&#8217;t mind fat.</em> But he owned his own house even if he&#8217;d been stuck with it because he never found a buyer. <em>I&#8217;ve seen him up in his window just playing that guitar for hours. He never goes </em>anywhere<em>. I&#8217;m going to introduce you.</em> I didn&#8217;t see much of her after that, and I can&#8217;t say I minded.</p>
<p>Then one day Sharon found herself a man of her own. He was barrel-chested, smoked a lot and didn&#8217;t say much. Let&#8217;s call him Dick.</p>
<p>By the time Dick had come around, even if it was for the sole purpose of trying to block my parking spot, Sharon had stopped sunning her wig outdoors, and never made another mention of Phil. I could have sworn I saw her duck into her apartment at least twice without the usual greeting when I pulled up.</p>
<p>It just so happens that I had begun dating around that time too. One day my man and I pulled up and saw Dick out front, sitting at Sharon&#8217;s table with a plastic cup clutched in his scaly, outsized paw. She must have stepped inside for something because there was another cup where her wig used to be.</p>
<p>My friend and I got out and said hi. Dick looked straight at us and said nothing. I figured maybe he was deaf and that accounted for his not speaking. I already knew he wasn&#8217;t blind because he&#8217;d seen his way clear enough to block my parking spot just fine in the past. I had my suspicions about his being dumb, but I won&#8217;t go there.</p>
<p>Once inside my place, I asked my friend if it had been my imagination, or did we just get dissed by Dick? My friend confirmed the latter.</p>
<p>Sharon&#8217;s beau reminded me of that man in the old battery commercials. He was the pseudo badass in the Members Only jacket who dared you to knock the thing off his shoulder. Dick was still wearing that jacket, and he was still carrying something on his shoulder too. From what I could tell, it looked like bitter resentment at passage of the Civil Rights Act.</p>
<p>For weeks, I scoured my memory of Sharon for all of her off-color comments and offenses I&#8217;d  overlooked out of neighborly courtesy, or a touch of too much permissiveness, or, frankly, apathy on my part. Plus, I thought, Sharon might be just like the rest of us, only she had fewer social censors. &#8216;Just like the rest of us&#8217; meant she was allowed to have her own opinions and be awkward sometimes, frequently misunderstood, human, and therefore always seeking some kind of connection. But <em>this?</em> Had she become so pickled in her twilight that she could invite this knuckle-dragging behemoth into her life and shut down whatever she had left of a free-thinking mind?</p>
<p>Based on what little I&#8217;d seen of Dick, I suspected he went home at night to leaf through dogeared supremacist literature and Nazi paraphernalia and to chip away at the cross he was itching to burn on somebody&#8217;s lawn or semi-covered carport one day.</p>
<p>Two more months went by like that, without really seeing or talking to my neighbor, and without missing her either. I&#8217;ve talked about the <a title="Victims" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/11/04/victims/" target="_blank">usefulness of building cases against people</a>, and I go on about <a title="P.S. I Love You" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/17/p-s-i-love-you-2/" target="_blank">love and neighbors</a> and <a title="The Deacon’s Boot" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/11/the-deacons-boot/" target="_blank">trying to do right by others</a> in a whole bunch of other essays, but this was another thing. This time we&#8217;re talking about issues really <em>really</em> close to home. So it&#8217;s different. Right?</p>
<p>Before I got through with Sharon in my mind, I&#8217;d whittled her down to a drunk and witless, badly-aging Southern belle, who also happened to be a flaming bigot to anybody unlike her &#8230; and her Dick. I&#8217;m not proud of it, and we all know I know better. It&#8217;s the <em>doing</em> part, that&#8217;s the tricky bit.</p>
<p>It was two weeks into the new year and I hadn&#8217;t seen Sharon&#8217;s car move once. It snowed and thawed and snowed again, and nothing. Even her beauty stand and her ashtray were gone. Despite my judgments, I started to wonder if she was okay, then dismissed the thoughts as they came. Until the day I pulled up and saw her lights on. Finally.</p>
<p>I got out of my car and started toward her door, backed up and thought twice about it, figuring if she was dead, then it was a next of kin who had turned on the lights and was handling her business. No matter how I played the scenario out in my mind, it came down to not being one bit of my business. Except that it was, and I knew it. So I knocked.</p>
<p>Another neighbor was already inside and opened the door. Sharon was sprawled across the couch, ready for an evening out, it seemed, in full makeup, three-quarter length leggings and slouchy asymmetrical tunic. She waved me in like she was the queen of Colorado holding court in her living room. Sharon&#8217;s right index finger was wrapped in a fat bandage and despite the glitzy earrings that hung to her shoulders, I noticed she wasn&#8217;t wearing her wig. She looked frail.</p>
<p>I said I&#8217;d been concerned because I hadn&#8217;t seen her car move in weeks, and told her to call me if she needed anything. Sharon smiled and said she&#8217;d been in the hospital for the last ten days on anti-biotics after surgery to remove a blood clot that could have killed her. She told me about a pre-existing condition that was slowly attacking her nervous system and how she&#8217;d have to find something to do now that she&#8217;d given up smoking. She wondered aloud how she&#8217;d pay without insurance. But lucky for her, she said, they only had to amputate a part of her index finger where the clot was and she could live with that.</p>
<p>Sharon thanked me for coming by. <em>I don&#8217;t know why no one else came,</em> she said shaking her head to one side and the other. <em>I&#8217;m nice to everybody, but I just &#8230; I almost died &#8230; I just don&#8217;t know.</em></p>
<p>I felt the grip of my own resentment toward her loosen. It didn&#8217;t all disappear like magic, but it took a load off of itself, and opened up room enough to be grateful for the fullness of my own health and to be glad my small action comforted her–no matter what the other assumptions had been–because what mattered in that moment was something else entirely.</p>
<p>I left my number on her notepad and urged her to use it if she needed to. Sharon thanked me again and told me she loved me as I turned to go. As I wrote this post I thought about the love King and Ghandi and Mother Theresa and Jesus and all the great teachers talked about and emulated in their own lives. I thought of <a title="P.S. I Love You" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/17/p-s-i-love-you-2/" target="_blank">the old lay preacher</a> and everybody who&#8217;d ever said something similar: that the only thing worth holding on to—and giving—was love.</p>
<p>Now take a second to think about your own neighbors. See what I mean?</p>
<p>Marianne Williamson said: <em>In every community there is work to be done. In every nation, there are wounds to heal. In every heart there is the power to do it.</em> What if you could access this power and get busy where you live right now? When you do, <em>if</em> you do, may you feel yourself breaking past your confines of bias and into that place where there&#8217;s room enough to turn to your neighbors, tell them you love them too, and mean it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
