		<item>
		<title>P.S. I Love You</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/VJU-p9WDLyA/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/17/p-s-i-love-you-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 17 Jan 2012 06:09:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1945</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Two years ago I convinced myself to go to an MLK open mic night full of stringy-haired boomers and aspiring hippies who read, sang, and recited their way across the creaking platform stage of a tiny coffee bar on the outskirts of Boulder, Colorado. I’m sure theirs wasn’t the only show in town, but the [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/MartinLutherKingJr.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="MartinLutherKingJr" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/MartinLutherKingJr.jpg" alt="" width="245" height="318" /></a></p>
<p>Two years ago I convinced myself to go to an MLK open mic night full of stringy-haired boomers and aspiring hippies who read, sang, and recited their way across the creaking platform stage of a tiny coffee bar on the outskirts of Boulder, Colorado. I’m sure theirs wasn’t the only show in town, but the local paper said it was the closest. So I went. And while I could fill pages with a creative inventory of characters who passed through that night, there’s an unforgettable man who bears mentioning here: the old lay preacher. I don&#8217;t remember his name, but he looked like a shorter, frailer version of Gandalf, the gray-haired wizard from Lord of the Rings.</p>
<p><span id="more-1945"></span></p>
<p>I first noticed him shuffling through the café in a way that made me wonder if he’d lost something on the floor of the darkened room. When he took to the makeshift stage, he ad libbed for more than twenty minutes on the virtues of kindness and brotherly love in a way that evoked oratorical skill of King, and it made him seem much bigger and stronger than he appeared. His words roused my inner activist from sleep, that part of me that wanted nothing more than to leap from behind my wall of indifference and align with something truly revolutionary and <em>on purpose</em>. The preacher held our attention as he spoke, and peered out from behind his sawtooth bangs to invite us deeper into his story.</p>
<p><em>Uh oh.</em> I got the distinct feeling this man was about to launch the audience participation part of his act. It’s all well and good until they ask you to do something. <em>Here we go&#8230; </em>I thought<em>.</em></p>
<p><em>Turn to your neighbor,</em> the old man said. And I did. <em>Now say, ‘Neighbor… .&#8217;&#8221;</em> I winced.</p>
<p><em>Neighbor&#8230;,</em> I said. It comforted me knowing that if things went poorly as a result of this impromptu social experiment, I could say <em>The preacher made me do it</em>. Usually I’m all too willing to make fun of myself for a good cause, but I was new to Boulder then, I didn&#8217;t know those people, it was a small room. But when you go out to a small place in a small town, and you plunk yourself down near the front, you should probably make room for things to happen. The upside of it was, my neighbor was handsome and friendly, and we’d already been flirting through the night. So, truth be told, I didn&#8217;t mind one bit turning to my neighbor. <em>Neighbor,</em> I said smiling.</p>
<p>We sat quietly, uncomfortably, looking at each other, grinning, nervous, waiting for everybody else to find and address their own neighbors. And then the old preacher gave us our next line, <em>I want you to look &#8216;em dead in the eye and say … &#8216;I love you.&#8217;</em></p>
<p>Say what?</p>
<p>We squirmed, and then, again, did as we were told. In that tight little space (yes, the room was contracting), we leaned in across the table to declare our love to each other—strangers!—and then to the entire bar full of people I&#8217;d probably never see again.  It was weird. I felt exposed; my face flushed hot; I liked it.</p>
<p>Years ago, a former meditation teacher approached me after seeing me at a school function. She hugged me and looked deep into my eyes and told me she loved me. I feel kind of dopey admitting it now, but the experience couldn’t have jarred me any more than if I&#8217;d been splashed in the face with salty ice water. I blinked and scanned for the proper response. She held me lovingly by my shoulders, and smiled. It was all I could do offer her a drippy squeak of a reply along the lines of, <em>Uh, thanks?</em></p>
<p>It was a full six months before I realized what had happened to me that day: my teacher had <em>seen</em> me. In what took all of a moment between us, she&#8217;d breezed right by everything I&#8217;d ever been taught or thought I knew about love or loving and voided my notion that love had to be earned or built over time, or was only to be shown when people were good and secure on all sides before we daring to share something so intimate. She gave me a gift that day, one that I turned over and chewed on until the light switch finally flipped: <em>I am lovable and worthy of love just because I </em>am! Whoa. I ran into her months later and gushed, <em>I finally get it!</em> I was giddy at my revelation. <em>And I love you, too!</em> I exclaimed. I wanted to tell her how profound her words had been, how they&#8217;d shown me how skewed my own notions of love and my receptivity to it were. I felt full; I wanted to beat my breast and burst into song. I cleared my throat. The teacher looked at me half-smiling and replied, <em>It took you this long, Kriste?</em></p>
<p>I see these moments with the teacher and the preacher as the <em>Namaste</em> principle at work: it the grace that floats in when the divine or higher part of ourselves recognizes or bows to the divine in others. It&#8217;s bigger than just <em>us</em> and it&#8217;s this guiding force that serves as the foundation for what leaders like Ghandi and King exemplified in their lifetimes and teach us still. They staked their lives on it and derived great power from it. They gave this gift to the people, <em>all</em> people, despite the resistance from their many adversaries. And with it, they changed the world. It&#8217;s loving the neighbors we don&#8217;t know—and the people we do know but don&#8217;t care much for—in equal measure. Including our enemies. Oh, <em>especially</em> the enemies.</p>
<p>I remember being super pissed off after an exchange with someone once. We were going rounds in a ridiculous power struggle and wore ourselves out sparring and sniping back and forth for days. I told my girlfriend Jewel about it, and anybody else who&#8217;d listen, snorting and fuming at all the ways I&#8217;d been wronged. Jewel heard me out and then told me to send that person love. <em>You&#8217;ve got to send &#8216;em love,</em> she said. She was so serene when she said it. I wanted to throttle her. I wanted to spit. I lost it. <em>Here we go again,</em> I grumbled. <em>What the </em>hell<em> is with these people trying to make me love and be happy and sing My Little Pony unicorn rainbow songs when they don&#8217;t get it?</em> <em>I am pissed off and I want me some justice!</em> The kicker was that each of these people: the preacher, the teacher, King and my friend were dead serious about invoking love as the elixir and<em> I</em> was the one who didn&#8217;t get it. At the time, I was like, <em>Fine. I&#8217;ll be over here, stewing in my juice, mounting my defense, while y&#8217;all twist your beads, grow your hair, and burn your incense—whatever.</em></p>
<p>And then, the miracle: I started to get it. Like drops from a leaky faucet over a dry sponge, one by one, my teachers (including the enemy) and the lessons they brought landed somewhere in my mind and eventually saturated my thinking. Eureka! Dr. King said: <em>I have decided to stick with love. Hate is too great a burden to bear.</em> I feel the truth of his words because he&#8217;s reminding me that to love each other is a conscious moment-by-moment decision that&#8217;s often difficult to get behind—but it&#8217;s always imperative. To me, this is what love is: it&#8217;s the real deal, the uncut stuff that breaks new ground, plants the seeds, feeds the people, and changes nations from the inside out. Hey, neighbor, break me off a piece of that, would you?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
