			<itunes:subtitle>Two years ago I convinced myself to go to an MLK open mic night full of stringy-haired boomers and aspiring hippies who read, sang, and recited their way across the creaking platform stage of a tiny coffee bar on the outskirts of Boulder, Colorado.</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>Two years ago I convinced myself to go to an MLK open mic night full of stringy-haired boomers and aspiring hippies who read, sang, and recited their way across the creaking platform stage of a tiny coffee bar on the outskirts of Boulder, Colorado. I’m sure theirs wasn’t the only show in town, but the local paper said it was the closest. So I went. And while I could fill pages with a creative inventory of characters who passed through that night, there’s an unforgettable man who bears mentioning here: the old lay preacher. I don't remember his name, but he looked like a shorter, frailer version of Gandalf, the gray-haired wizard from Lord of the Rings.



I first noticed him shuffling through the café in a way that made me wonder if he’d lost something on the floor of the darkened room. When he took to the makeshift stage, he ad libbed for more than twenty minutes on the virtues of kindness and brotherly love in a way that evoked oratorical skill of King, and it made him seem much bigger and stronger than he appeared. His words roused my inner activist from sleep, that part of me that wanted nothing more than to leap from behind my wall of indifference and align with something truly revolutionary and on purpose. The preacher held our attention as he spoke, and peered out from behind his sawtooth bangs to invite us deeper into his story.

Uh oh. I got the distinct feeling this man was about to launch the audience participation part of his act. It’s all well and good until they ask you to do something. Here we go... I thought.

Turn to your neighbor, the old man said. And I did. Now say, ‘Neighbor… .'" I winced.

Neighbor..., I said. It comforted me knowing that if things went poorly as a result of this impromptu social experiment, I could say The preacher made me do it. Usually I’m all too willing to make fun of myself for a good cause, but I was new to Boulder then, I didn't know those people, it was a small room. But when you go out to a small place in a small town, and you plunk yourself down near the front, you should probably make room for things to happen. The upside of it was, my neighbor was handsome and friendly, and we’d already been flirting through the night. So, truth be told, I didn't mind one bit turning to my neighbor. Neighbor, I said smiling.

We sat quietly, uncomfortably, looking at each other, grinning, nervous, waiting for everybody else to find and address their own neighbors. And then the old preacher gave us our next line, I want you to look 'em dead in the eye and say … 'I love you.'

Say what?

We squirmed, and then, again, did as we were told. In that tight little space (yes, the room was contracting), we leaned in across the table to declare our love to each other—strangers!—and then to the entire bar full of people I'd probably never see again.  It was weird. I felt exposed; my face flushed hot; I liked it.

Years ago, a former meditation teacher approached me after seeing me at a school function. She hugged me and looked deep into my eyes and told me she loved me. I feel kind of dopey admitting it now, but the experience couldn’t have jarred me any more than if I'd been splashed in the face with salty ice water. I blinked and scanned for the proper response. She held me lovingly by my shoulders, and smiled. It was all I could do offer her a drippy squeak of a reply along the lines of, Uh, thanks?

It was a full six months before I realized what had happened to me that day: my teacher had seen me. In what took all of a moment between us, she'd breezed right by everything I'd ever been taught or thought I knew about love or loving and voided my notion that love had to be earned or built over time, or was only to be shown when people were good and secure on all sides before we daring to share something so intimate. She gave me a gift that day, one that I turned over and chewed on until the light switch finally flipped: I am lovable and worthy of love just because I am! Whoa.</itunes:summary>
