		<item>
		<title>New Year Revolutions</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/VBxDLOGk5pY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/12/31/new-year-revolutions/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 01 Jan 2012 02:37:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1864</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The time is ripe for a revolt. I&#8217;m talking, like, raining down change more swift than the Arab Spring and the autumnal fall of dictators a world away. I&#8217;m talking more peace-inducing than flower power, greater than Beyoncé&#8217;s baby and Demi&#8217;s pending divorce. This is huge. And it&#8217;s not a movement for those people over [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/carpe-diem.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1869" title="carpe diem" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/carpe-diem.jpg" alt="" width="316" height="380" /></a>The time is ripe for a revolt. I&#8217;m talking, like, raining down change more swift than the Arab Spring and the autumnal fall of dictators a world away. I&#8217;m talking more peace-inducing than flower power, greater than Beyoncé&#8217;s baby and Demi&#8217;s pending divorce. This is huge. And it&#8217;s not a movement for <em>those</em> people <em>over there</em>, whether it&#8217;s on the other side of the world or across your street. This is insurgence at its best, an unmitigated mutiny of the highest order, and your presence is required.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m talking about YOU stirring up some change right now in the comfort of your own home, for no money down. It won&#8217;t cost you anything but your lethargy and defeat. What you&#8217;ll stand to gain in return for staging your own revolt is its own reward: it&#8217;s the gift of taking your place in the struggle against mediocrity, boredom, cluelessness and your same old stuff. It&#8217;s simple, really, this revolutionary action plan of mine. I call it Showing Up.</p>
<p><span id="more-1864"></span></p>
<p>As I wrote this post, women of all ages and abilities were taking to the streets of Egypt telling their leaders – and the world – Enough. We&#8217;re through fueling your machine that only serves to bulldoze and trample us. We will make ourselves visible; we&#8217;ll tell the world we&#8217;re here and we will keep speaking out. As they marched, they called women out of their homes and down from balconies to add their voices to the outcry. They wanted to create some serious change so they Showed Up.</p>
<p>Just down my street, and at a great many city centers throughout the United States, frustrated citizens have pitched a great many fits – and tents – in an act of solidarity with their ideological comrades-in-arms to tell leadership, <em>We&#8217;re tired of your stalled, go-nowhere government and, guess what, we&#8217;re not going anywhere, either.</em> There&#8217;s a rash of uprising that has broken out in similar fashion around the world and average citizens are decrying widespread corruption as commonplace, they&#8217;re calling for an end to blanket defaults on promises, if not platitudes, made by power brokers in more prosperous times. In one collective global gesture, people everywhere are disrupting bad business as usual by Showing Up.</p>
<p>In other areas of the Year In Revolt and breakaway from the everyday, three extraordinary women were jointly awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of &#8220;their non-violent struggle for the safety of women and for women’s rights to full participation in peace-building work.&#8221;</p>
<p>Journalist, politician, and human rights activist Tawakel Karman led protests for freedom of the press during uprisings in Yemen. President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf is that Liberia&#8217;s first female leader and the first woman president in all of Africa. She&#8217;s scored unprecedented reforms in debt relief and post-conflict reconciliation. Leymah Gbowee, also Liberian, is a civil rights activist, whose coalition of Muslim and Christian women staging sit-ins, prayer vigils, and appeals to rebels to sign a peace deal ultimately brought an end to their fighting. These women saw a need and assumed responsibility for their futures by Showing Up.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s no way a single post could do justice to even a handful of the revolutions and revolutionaries that rocked our worlds this year, but I touch on them because they illustrate my point that change is indeed happening all around us at every moment and, lest we be left feeling left out of the sweeping shifts in going on around the globe, I&#8217;d also like to point out that changes are also happening to us, whether or not we participate in them consciously.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;d like to shift and shape the landscape of your life in the New Year, I&#8217;d like to propose a few ways to help you make it happen—and I mean, starting now. Going in, you should know that your personal revolution won&#8217;t require any travel. Scratch that: your revolt may demand that you take the metaphorical path less traveled or that you blaze a new trail altogether. And while your revolution may not necessarily call for any official training and won&#8217;t cost you a dime, you will be called upon to pay close attention to your behavior and to exercise, strengthen, and develop your powers of discernment and choice on a daily basis.</p>
<p>I&#8217;d like to guarantee you won&#8217;t come to any bodily harm once you start shaking things up, but that depends on how you carry out my forthcoming proposition. I cannot be held responsible if you experience some gentle bruising when random admirers start bear hugging you, high-fiving and hoisting you up on their shoulders, singing your praises, chanting your name in the streets. I might feel bad if your ears ring for the next few months as fans fawn and coo at the waves of change you&#8217;re instigating, but so it goes. I don&#8217;t have to tell you there&#8217;s the certainty of cold shoulders and occasional crickets that will surface as you revolt against the tyranny of inertia and low expectations because naysayers are to be expected when shift happens. Alas, they are the norm. But the presumption here, dear reader, is that you are anything but normal.</p>
<p>In the spirit of genuine revolution and Showing Up, I&#8217;d like to offer you:</p>
<p><strong>10 tactics to change the world from where you are. Right now. Today. Beginning of story.</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. GIVE UP.</strong> Let go of your old notions of how things should be. You know that saying, &#8220;Don&#8217;t should on yourself?&#8221; Yeah, taking on guilt and pressure for what&#8217;s not yours to manage siphons your creativity and gets you nowhere. Forget about trying to control other folks&#8217; behavior and outcomes that don&#8217;t concern you. Let them have their own lessons and get busy figuring out how best to mind your business. Remember that they may be trying to create some change of their own, so give them room! You&#8217;ll be doing them and you a favor in the end. Plus, you&#8217;ll be surprised at how much time you&#8217;ve freed up for ticking things off your list instead of ticking people off around you.</p>
<p><strong>2. HOLD ON.</strong> Put another way, don&#8217;t abandon what you want. And if you&#8217;re letting other people trick you into thinking your dreams are dumb, knock it off. And, worse yet, if you try to get other people to tell you your dreams don&#8217;t count, like in <a title="Reflections" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/02/11/reflections/"><strong>this example</strong></a>, then you and I will officially have a problem. If you want to be or do something, figure out how you can Show Up in big and small ways to create that change. Right now. Want to write? Then write (soon as you finish reading this, of course). Want to run? Run. Start by walking and take it from there. Want to save? Then save. And keep at it. Consistency is one of the greatest gifts you can give to the realization of your dream. Inspiration is often the fuel, occasionally rides shotgun, and can even feel like it&#8217;s D.O.A. some days, so it&#8217;s better to know that from the start. Do what you can in whatever measure you can; it all adds up. There&#8217;s no way around putting in the work to get where you want to go (#8). The upside? There&#8217;s no sweeter reward than feasting on the fruits of your own labor (#7).</p>
<p><strong>3. FLIP SCRIPTS.</strong> Another great way to revolutionize your life is to change your perspective. Got a nagging problem that seems to be blocking you at every turn? Try looking at it with fresh eyes. Imagine your creative block(s) as a person; ask it/him/her what it wants from you. Sometimes what look like our greatest obstacles contain our greatest stepping stones, not to mention answers and epiphanies. Let&#8217;s say you&#8217;ve issues with someone. Rather than relying on the defense of a sharp tongue or cold shoulder, try putting yourself in that person&#8217;s shoes. Try to understand how miscommunication, hurt feelings or their own old beliefs and esteem might account for the friction. Give yourself permission to disagree or even dislike it and then let it go (#1). And don&#8217;t stop there. If you can&#8217;t come to peace with that person or issue in that moment, at least give yourself credit for responding in a new way. Be mindful of the boomerang effect and send love along with everything you do. Then watch how it ripples into your own revolutionized life!</p>
<p><strong>4. LOOK ALIVE.</strong> There&#8217;s no such thing as a narcoleptic revolutionary. Meaning, when&#8217;s the last time you saw a freedom fighter asleep on the front lines? When you Show Up to your life, it means you&#8217;re paying attention to the world around you in a new way. What kind of language do you use in your conversations? What roles are you playing in your relationships? How are your actions reflecting or projecting the real you? How much are you &#8216;putting up&#8217; with simply because you want to &#8216;keep&#8217; the peace? Here&#8217;s a hint: You&#8217;re not experiencing any real peace if you&#8217;re withholding your feelings because you fear someone&#8217;s possible response.</p>
<p><strong>5. KEEP QUIET.</strong> Truth: you can&#8217;t tell everybody what you&#8217;re up to all the time. As a self-confessed <em>semi-full-disclosurist</em>, I tend to talk too much. And when I do, I find the energy I&#8217;ve expended in all my telling and sharing and &#8216;splaining runs the risk of dissipating the energy I could be applying to moving my plans forward in a real, measurable way while staying on track with my goals. It takes focus and a commitment to own your own agenda and to cultivate it, away from the heavy winds of doubt, the backdraft of blowhards, and the burning glare of stink eyes and unsolicited opinion. So the next time you feel the urge to tell all, hush up for a minute and ask yourself what&#8217;s the truest and best use of your time in that moment.</p>
<p><strong>6. SPEAK UP.</strong> I&#8217;ve covered this territory in a <strong><a title="Small Talk" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/12/16/small-talk/">previous entry</a></strong>, but even if this was the only topic I ever wrote about for the rest of my days, I could never come close to wearing out the value of finding, hearing, and following your own voice. There&#8217;s a difference between keeping quiet and being silenced, and you won&#8217;t know which mode you&#8217;re in unless you&#8217;re looking alive in the moment (#4) and considering the situation from a new angle (#3) and resisting the urge or habit of judging others for how they respond to you (#1). You&#8217;ve also got to be willing to trust your own heart enough to know have to believe in YOU and to go in the direction of your calling (#2). Whether or not you use your words to speak up for yourself — because it&#8217;s our energy and actions that do all the talking, in case you didn&#8217;t already know — keep in mind that when you&#8217;re truly focused on what you want — when you&#8217;re really minding your business, you have seriously Shown Up and that message rings out loud and clear.</p>
<p><strong>7. GO EASY</strong>. For all this talk of Showing Up and outward revolutionizing, I have to include this interior piece in the process: easy does it. I can personally point you to lots of my own false starts dropped balls littering the roadside of my revolutionary, evolutionary path, like <strong><a title="Spare Some Change?" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/03/05/spare-some-change/">here</a></strong>, <strong><a title="Seeds of…Change?" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/04/22/seeds-of-change/">here</a></strong>, and <strong><a title="Ruts" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/05/30/in-a-rut/">here</a></strong> for starters, but even when we fumble, we have to keep in mind that the game goes on, that we&#8217;re not in it to be perfect, but to be engaged. Take time to give yourself credit for venturing beyond your comfort zone and realize that every conscious step (#4) taken toward your goal is a Victory. I&#8217;ve touched on this <a title="I won! I won!" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/03/24/i-won-i-won/"><strong>here</strong></a> and it was a super reminder that no matter where I find myself on my personal timeline, I&#8217;m right where I need to be. And knowing that is a gift in and of itself.</p>
<p><strong>8. PLAY HARD.</strong> When you&#8217;re going for the gold of your goals, you&#8217;ve got to make sure it&#8217;s a long-term game. I&#8217;m talking even longer than baseball. There&#8217;s no way around it; the overnight discovery and fantasy of &#8216;making it&#8217; takes years of work. In his thought-provoking book on genius, game changers and trailblazers, Outliers, my man Malcolm Gladwell tells us through a series of painstaking research, interviews, and personal history that overnight success takes about 10,000 hours. That breaks down to 416.6666667 days, not including breaks for cyberjiving, sleep or showering. That&#8217;s full on 24/7. So when you spread those hours out into a real-life timeline, you&#8217;ll see that it&#8217;s doable, and it&#8217;s going to require your best efforts. So hunker down and get your mind and behind in the game, that is, if you&#8217;re playing to win. And by winning, I could have easily said self-actualizing or following through or believing in yourself. I just use that term because I&#8217;m fond of an occasional sports analogy like keeping eyes on balls, leaving things on fields, going long, and all those other gamey go-get-&#8217;em-isms.</p>
<p><strong>9. FAIL BETTER.</strong> Mahatma Gandhi once said, “My imperfections and failures are as much a blessing from God as my successes and my talents and I lay them both at his feet.” I often talk about having gratitude for everything, like <strong><a title="Thanks" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/11/26/thanks/">here</a></strong>, and I like what he said because it reminds us there might just be a greater plan, like <a title="Origins" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/04/18/origins/"><strong>here</strong></a>, that we&#8217;re all a part of, no matter how worthy or not we perceive ourselves to be. If and when we can wrap our minds around the fact that love in action and humility are powerful allies in the Revolt, and that success and failure are two sides of the same coin, then we become unstoppable. As an individual who Showed Up, told his truth to the establishment and mobilized a movement that rippled around the world, Gandhi is a revolutionary whose life reminds us it&#8217;s ALL good (#3) and plainly lays out what we&#8217;re capable of when we Show Up: we can fail a little bit better every time we try.</p>
<p><strong>10. REPEAT 1-9.</strong> Of course I could go on about how to Show Up and change your life and the world from the inside out, but I hope you get my point(s). Besides, I&#8217;ve got my own work to do. Now let&#8217;s get busy giving up, leaving folks alone, keeping quiet, going easy, failing, letting go, and having a truly revolting 2012!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
<p>You might also be interested in:</p>
