		<item>
		<title>Affirm This!</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/EHTCDRxFGdc/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/11/20/affirm-this/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 20 Nov 2011 20:25:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1788</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[For all my positive talk, I have my issues with affirmations on precisely that point: they&#8217;re all talk. There was this guy once—Eddie. Even if you pressed me, I couldn&#8217;t tell you exactly how I found him, and I have no idea how to locate him now; it was a totally random web crawl. Eddie [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/298456_2651762298556_1390715345_3019959_1905888180_n.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1789" title="298456_2651762298556_1390715345_3019959_1905888180_n" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/298456_2651762298556_1390715345_3019959_1905888180_n-300x173.jpg" alt="" width="388" height="224" /></a></p>
<p>For all my positive talk, I have my issues with affirmations on precisely that point: they&#8217;re all talk. There was this guy once—Eddie. Even if you pressed me, I couldn&#8217;t tell you exactly how I found him, and I have no idea how to locate him now; it was a totally random web crawl. Eddie had an internet show devoted to affirmations and each week he&#8217;d spend about ten minutes going over a handful of handpicked one-liners based on a chosen theme for the next seven days. His platform was simple and straightforward: <em>Hi, I&#8217;m Eddie and here are today&#8217;s affirmations. They&#8217;re blah, blah </em>and<em> blah.</em> Then he&#8217;d do about fifteen repetitions and sign off with something like, <em>Okay, I&#8217;ll see you next week.</em></p>
<p><span id="more-1788"></span></p>
<p>For a few weeks I tuned in regularly and became fascinated with Eddie, not fascinated by what he was saying so much, but it was his delivery. I don&#8217;t know if it was intentional, but Eddie&#8217;s voice was a solid cross between the flat intonation of the eyedrops guy—you know, Clear Eyes—and the Dunkin man from back in the day. Remember him? He&#8217;d get out of bed, shuffle off to work each morning moaning, <em>Time to make the donuts.</em> That&#8217;s what hooked me—I couldn&#8217;t tell if Eddie was joking. But, he must have been doing something right because I was right there with him each week for a month—right up until he dropped the whole project.</p>
<p>In as few words as possible, Eddie returned several weeks later and said that repeating all of those positive messages over and over had begun to bring stuff up for him that he didn&#8217;t like and that made him see he needed to step away from it all while he <em>dealt with it</em> and made sense of what was happening to him. I wish he&#8217;d have called me because I have a few ideas about what he was experiencing.</p>
<p>I liken Eddie&#8217;s situation to spring cleaning. In the beginning it&#8217;s the innocuous anticipation of the new season, affirmations are. <em>This time it&#8217;s going to be positive, fresh, revitalized and vibrant,</em> we say. And so it&#8217;s only right that we get all frothy and lightheaded about the new season of potential. We&#8217;re going to rearrange the furniture, clear out clutter, and beat the curtains. We get a taste for how things could be and start to dream and lay out our vision of the sparkling new future.</p>
<p>In Eddie&#8217;s case, and in lots of our cases, we try a few phrases of possibility on for size before launching into the work. It&#8217;s a sort of preliminary assessment taken before the official launch. How about this: <em>I am fit and loaded and everybody loves me&#8230;</em> or something like <em>I am popular and fabulous and happy on the inside&#8230;</em> Eventually we land on a couple of focus points and start in on the affirmative cleanup. And depending on how big our respective projects are, we can expect to have an equal amount of dust and very likely, resistance creeping in too.</p>
<p>In the literal act of spring cleaning and clean sweeping, it&#8217;s easy enough to see that if we&#8217;re to clear out the old, we&#8217;ll need to bring in the proper tools and cleaning agents before engaging with what needs to be trashed and rearranged. It&#8217;s unglamorous and tiresome, we know this going in. So we grab the bucket and glove ourselves up to the elbows and get busy. The energy part of it is parallel on this point. Only problem, though, is it&#8217;s easy to get defeated once we start to dislodge the old ideas and beliefs about what we&#8217;re capable and deserving of.</p>
<p>If we&#8217;ve ever worked together, you know I&#8217;m all about the multi-pronged approach. I&#8217;ll offer you at least half a dozen ways to get to your goal or to put you back on track to the thing you&#8217;ve been off course on. I&#8217;m good at that, naturally. You might even say I&#8217;m an expert at getting off track and losing the way and shrinking back from the dust I&#8217;ve kicked up in various corners of my own life. I do so not because I&#8217;m a loser, I do it for <em>you</em>. Think of it as me gathering information in the field on your behalf.</p>
<p>So, the multi prongs. I&#8217;m convinced it&#8217;s never about doing just one thing to create and sustain major changes in our lives, because it&#8217;s just not. No offense to Eddie, but Eddie only focused on telling himself great things that he had too little experience of in his life up to that point order to make an impact on his then current life. There he was saying, again without a trace of irony or enthusiasm, <em>I am fit and wealthy and everybody loves me&#8230;</em> when it’s possible he didn&#8217;t have an exercise plan in place or maybe spent too much time and money on his Xbox, which means that even if everyone did love him—because what&#8217;s <em>not</em> to love about a man devoted to his affirmations no matter how temporary?—it&#8217;s not a stretch to say he might have been isolating himself without realizing it and perpetuating the same past patterns he was trying to sweep out of his life. So when the dusty old thoughts and stuffy <em>un</em>affirmative ideas about himself started to kick in and blur his vision, rather than reaching for the energetic multi-prongs of his bucket and scrubbing bubbles, he buckled and called the whole thing off.</p>
<p>Last year I led a workshop on this topic of setting and achieving goals when a woman in the front row shot her hand up and cried foul. She was pissed off about positive thinking and couldn&#8217;t bear to hear another New Agey spin on it. She&#8217;d been frustrated by all the talk minus the action and I couldn&#8217;t blame her. It was my first experience with a spiritual heckler and, man, was it good. She was in my face, pitched forward and listening in with her whole body as I spoke. She couldn&#8217;t have been more focused on me than if she&#8217;d borrowed extra eyeballs and trained them on me too.</p>
<p><em>Yes, you&#8217;re right,</em> I shot back. <em>It</em> is <em>total b.s. if all we&#8217;re doing is talking. As a matter of fact,</em> I said, <em>if I hear another chirpy do-gooder telling me to &#8216;Let my light shine,&#8217; without preparing me for the shadows, I might have to break something</em>. And I thought the room was quiet before—</p>
<p>I told the group about the importance of giving ourselves messages that our brains can actually make room for. Otherwise, if we tell ourselves things we don&#8217;t actually believe, we do more harm than good, so why bother? So, instead of saying stuff like, <em>I&#8217;m awesome</em> when you generally think you&#8217;re a joke, it might be better to open the door from where you are to say something more truly affirming like, <em>Every day, I&#8217;m getting better</em> or <em>I&#8217;m willing to have an awesome life</em> and how about this: <em>I give myself permission to be awesome.</em> And don&#8217;t stop there, because &#8230; Eddie, remember?</p>
<p>When we begin the work of change, we&#8217;ve got to make sure we have supports—people, resources, fallbacks, shameless ploys, etc.—in place to help facilitate our transition. If you&#8217;re affirming your awesomeness, for example, then act like you know it. Replace those ratty grandma drawers and mateless holey socks with new and beautiful unmentionables because, underneath it all, you <em>know</em> you&#8217;re worth it. Frame awesome photos and art and put them where you&#8217;ll have constant visuals of awesome times. Scale back on the non-awesome things you put in your body. Remember what the Staple Singers said about eradicating air pollution: <em>Put your hand o&#8217;er your mouth when you cough, that&#8217;ll help the solution.</em> Your actions matter and every bit counts. And pay attention to the places you go when the fabulous feelings fade—because they will sometimes. Do you reach for sweets, alcohol, or non-foodish material things? Instead of dealing with your disappointment, do you displace it and let it spread out over your life like a giant schmear of funk that permeates everything you do?</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s another great energetic prong of awesomeness: project the feelings you&#8217;d like to experience on to the world around you. Tell a friend, whom you happen to think is awesome, that they&#8217;re just that. Watch this feeling expand and see how good it makes you feel too. It&#8217;s going to be awkward at first, <em>walking</em> the talk of your affirmations and edging outside of your comfort zone, letting yourself be playful with the possibilities—but that&#8217;s where the magic happens. Affirm your affirmations in word <em>and</em> deed. Walk your talk rather than watching and waiting on your talk to walk across the room and affirm things for you.</p>
<p>Infuse your world with great new energy so that it&#8217;s waiting to greet you throughout the day. And when old ideas start to kick up, not only will you know you&#8217;re on to something good, and that those thoughts have been stirred not to take you down but to be swept out like any other mental, actual, or imagined elemental form of dust bunny, but you&#8217;ll be able to counter with <em>evidence</em> that you are indeed <em>getting better all the time</em>. Just look at your matching socks, the lovely images around you now, your happy best buds who know you care, your new underwear. See?</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
<p>PS Thanks to Sherry for letting me borrow her image above!</p>
