		<item>
		<title>Do You Need Anybody?</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/Lbm-gmzDZnk/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/10/23/do-you-need-anybody/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 24 Oct 2011 00:54:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=436</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[&#160; There are times when only a song will do. And this is one of them. For as far back as I can remember Joe Cocker, I&#8217;ve linked the the grizzled crooner to his scratchy rendition of &#8216;You Are So Beautiful&#8217; (and, as of the eighties, the gospelesque hit &#8216;Up Where We Belong&#8217;). But it&#8217;s [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/gQLtCoh5EaI" frameborder="0" width="420" height="315"></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There are times when only a song will do. And this is one of them.</p>
<p>For as far back as I can remember Joe Cocker, I&#8217;ve linked the the grizzled crooner to his scratchy rendition of &#8216;You Are So Beautiful&#8217; (and, as of the eighties, the gospelesque hit &#8216;Up Where We Belong&#8217;). But it&#8217;s <em>this</em> tune, &#8216;With A Little Help From My Friends&#8217; that really sings to me. It&#8217;s about the everlasting importance of friendship and I&#8217;m loving it right about now. I know, we&#8217;ve already got the Beatles version. And we&#8217;ve got Dionne Warwick, Elton John, Gladys Knight, Stevie Wonder and friends who came along with their megahit &#8216;That&#8217;s What Friends are For&#8217;, and we can&#8217;t leave out Bill Withers&#8217; classic, &#8216;Lean on Me&#8217;. They all tug at my heartstrings, but I have my reasons for pulling Joe out of the bag this time around. The main one: he&#8217;s clearly unstable.</p>
<p><span id="more-436"></span></p>
<p>To watch him perform, all jerky and flailing like a palsied fish out of water, I often imagine myself asking him, &#8220;Would it kill you to actually sing sometimes, Joe? You know, without all of the breathless grunting and urgency?&#8221; He&#8217;d seem thrown, rendered momentarily speechless as though I&#8217;d been the only one to ever ask him this. Then with an involuntary shake of his shoulders, he&#8217;d reply in my mind, &#8220;Yeah, Kriste, yeah it just might.&#8221;</p>
<p>I was drawn to this video like a rubbernecker to the scene of an accident: I couldn&#8217;t tell what was going on, but I knew whatever it was was big and very likely dangerous if I got too close. And that&#8217;s exactly the way Joe Cocker sings. It&#8217;s an immediate, messy collision of raw emotion and spectacle that demands your attention and impacts you in ways can&#8217;t readily explain.</p>
<p>I may be attributing too much to his delivery—and I&#8217;m willing to acknowledge my own singing experience makes me hyper-aware of dramatic onstage mannerisms like his—and yet, at the end of the day, I know this man <em>knows</em> what he&#8217;s singing about.</p>
<p>I confess I don&#8217;t know all of the words to this tune, nor have I bothered to look them up. Still, I&#8217;m certain everything I need to know is right there in the title. And the refrain. Which leads me at last to my most pressing question: Do you need anybody?</p>
<p>Given all the messages of high-achieving, self-directed, living-the-dream can-doism that come from the world around me, I often feel like I&#8217;m supposed to know it all, have it all, and be all things to more than a few people&#8230;all without ever needing anyone else along the way. In the sense of being responsible for myself by making a living, paying my bills, and doing whatever I see fit to do for myself, I&#8217;d say, no, I don&#8217;t <em>need</em> anyone to take care of me. Nor do I require anyone else to provide my sense of my esteem or value either. I&#8217;ve got that relatively well covered, too. And even in knowing that I&#8217;m already energetically connected to everyone, there&#8217;s still a sizable chunk of living that requires person-to-person connection to make things interesting, not to mention worthwhile.</p>
<p>So, when&#8217;s the last time someone besides me encouraged you to fearlessly extend yourself to other people for goodness&#8217; sake?</p>
<p>Even on my recent foray back into the dating scene, as I was tweaking my online profile, I felt oddly wrong for saying I ultimately wanted a partner to share my life with. Why? Because, if I&#8217;m honest, I run the risk of appearing desperate, too needy, and, consequently, about as appealing as an old hand towel.</p>
<p>Reaching out for anything from other people has the potential to make us feel uncomfortable at best. Not to mention weak in exactly all the ways that run counter to the self-selfing teachings of culture.</p>
<p>That&#8217;s why I can&#8217;t look away from Joe Cocker. Because, for all of his thrashing about and painful articulation, he puts his heart on the line without a care for his tatty appearance and garbled renditions. In doing so, he reminds me what we must look like to each other when we risk our own vulnerability to make real and lasting contact with the folks who matter most around us.</p>
<p>Like Joe, my emotional delivery occasionally comes across as a trembling mess of nerves and rambling non sequiturs, but I&#8217;m trusting my heart is in the right place, and that counts for everything. It&#8217;s not always easy extending myself in this way, but who am I—who are any of us, really—without relationships?</p>
<p>I like to think the people I know and love who also know and love me know that I know they really <em>do</em> help me get by by sharing themselves with me in loving ways and that, while I may not be perfect or consistently clever, they don&#8217;t hold it against me if I&#8217;m a sputtering mess on account of they&#8217;re forgiving, human, loyal, and oh so tolerant. And patient&#8230;even when I don&#8217;t make sense. Kind of like just now. Thanks for the reminder, Joe.</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
