		<item>
		<title>Hold That Door!</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/Vywr0B2ok8w/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/10/08/hold-that-door-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 08 Oct 2011 14:00:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1716</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[For the past three decades and then some—ever since I got the hang of running my mouth—I’ve been trying in vain to get my mother to do my bidding. But it remains one of life’s great mysteries why she never bent to my will. It’s beyond me why she has chosen to live her life [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Door.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1727" title="Door" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/Door-300x223.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="223" /></a><br />
For the past three decades and then some—ever since I got the hang of running my mouth—I’ve been trying in vain to get my mother to do my bidding. But it remains one of life’s great mysteries why she never bent to my will. It’s beyond me why she has chosen to live her life as though she were a self-directed individual with a mind and agenda of her own.</p>
<p><span id="more-1716"></span></p>
<p>When ma retired more than a decade ago, I did all I could to encourage her participation in activities beyond work and us ‘kids’. She wasn’t impressed. <em>Ma, you gotta take an interest</em>, I said, never initially bothering to specify what I thought she should be interested in. <em>Get out there</em>, I urged her. <em>Go date. Look </em>alive,<em> woman! Volunteer, socialize, learn a language</em>, I insisted. <em>Do</em> something, <em>ma</em>! Whenever I thought about her, which was often, I wrote notes, and phoned home from wherever I was in the world—in between my own adventures—to assess her status and gently clobber her with my attempts to pack the open calendar of her newly retired life.</p>
<p>She wasn&#8217;t having it.</p>
<p>Naturally, I stepped up my plan, drafting to-do lists (you know I&#8217;m infamous for my lists, honey), providing phone numbers, and slipping in the sobering statistics and manufactured facts about retirees who—by not remaining active in their golden years—ultimately retired from life itself after leaving the workforce. Having nearly reached my limit, I opted, as any keenly desperate strategist would, for overt tactics of fear and intimidation. <em>Did you know</em>, I said with much conviction as I could muster, <em>the FBI did a study that said life expectancy of retired people who don&#8217;t stay active after leaving the workforce is only 5 years</em>?</p>
<p>Still unmoved by this latest dump of misinformation, she replied, <em>What makes you think I want to </em>do<em> anything, Kriste? I been</em> doing<em> all my life. And I’m</em> tired. There aren’t many occasions when you’ll find me short for things to say, but that one shut me up pretty good.</p>
<p>After recovering from my mom’s ungracious outburst (and world-weary expression of her deeper personal truth, which I was powerless to fix), I grudgingly decided that, after decades of trying to run my mom’s life, I had to allow that maybe she knew what was best for her. Maybe, I considered, she could run her life without the intrusion of my unsolicited statistics, persistent lists, and thinly veiled demands to Move It. It was a difficult fistful of pills to swallow, but I was out of the nest living a life of my own and had to let my mom fly—or not—as she saw fit.</p>
<p>Then one day, not having fully and totally nor finally given up on the attempt to resurrect and direct my mom’s social life, I sent her a memoir I’d hoped would change <em>everything</em>. It was the story of a divorced, freshly retired teacher who—despite her many attempts at ‘staying busy’ by volunteering and senior activities—she got blindsided by a sudden desire to have sex and maybe even fall in love after so many decades spent on the shelf immersed in other things.</p>
<p>Bingo! <em>Just what my mother needs</em>, I proclaimed. <em>Sex!</em> I don’t give up easy.</p>
<p>I love that memoir because our heroine, Jane Juska, is a woman after my own heart. Some would say she was well beyond the age of ‘knowing better’,  past 60, and she still looked at her life as an adventure and knew that, even though she was clueless about getting into social circulation again—let alone getting into bed with someone new—she went for it anyway. She anted&#8217;d up and duked it out through the pages of her story and invited us in for the ride, so to speak. The book: <em>A Round-Heeled Woman: My Late-Life Adventures in Sex and Romance</em>. It was the perfect gift for any mother from a concerned daughter with her mom&#8217;s well-being in mind. I made a special trip to the post office just to send it off.</p>
<p>Once I’d given her enough time to read and marinate on the book, I called ma and engaged her in the following discussion:</p>
<p><strong>ME:</strong> So, ma, did you get that book I sent you?</p>
<p><strong>MA: </strong>What book?</p>
<p><strong>ME:</strong> You know, the one about that retired teacher who places a personal ad looking for sex. Remember?</p>
<p><strong>MA:</strong> Oh. That.</p>
<p><strong>ME:</strong> Yeah.</p>
<p>(Crickets.)</p>
<p><strong>ME:</strong> What did you think?</p>
<p><strong>MA:</strong> I read that first chapter, and as soon as she started getting racy, I couldn’t go any further. I had to put that book down. I shut the door on that part of my life a long time ago.</p>
<p>(Cue the sound of slamming of doors and cacophonous padlocking hysteria in the distance.)</p>
<p>With that, our conversation turned, as it so often did, to the whether—as in whether or not I’d met ‘Mr. Wonderful,’ and when I was coming home.</p>
<p>I’ve been thinking a lot about this notion of willfully closing doors to parts of my life. As a short-term solution or response it kind of makes sense. For example, suffering any kind of loss or disappointment is hardly a call to throw open the doors of one’s heart in search of more emotional rough-handling and whupass. I know I&#8217;m never keen on the idea of getting back out there wherever <em>there</em> is, only to feed my heart to what look like lions, and if I&#8217;m feeling wounded, I say screw any euphemistic chatter of romance. Emotional recovery and healing have their place and they take time. As long as they don&#8217;t take too much of it.</p>
<p>When you close the door to your heart, you may as well collapse in a heap, turn out the lights and forward your mail because you are effectively done at that point, you hear? D-O-N-E. I won’t lie; I sometimes look back and wonder how come this or that relationship of the past went bust, or why I behaved badly, if at all. And the more time I spend with ghosts, the more I see my responses steeped in fear, taking center stage like an horrific tragicomedy featuring me in all the up close, unflattering lead roles.</p>
<p>Oh, look! there’s me as Angela Bassett, burning down my house in a rage against the transgressions of a good man gone bad. How about me as Julia Roberts as the girl asking the boy to love the girl only to hear the record scratch during his loud and painfully protracted real-life <em>ambivilanche</em>. Then there’s me as Jennifer Lopez in profile during any given scene, forgetting my lines and hearing the hiss of my overexposed ass going flat on camera. Not pretty.</p>
<p>I can tell you in the full faith of my innermost conviction that the key to experiencing love and joy and romance and all of the goodies means that no matter what, I have to keep the doors of my heart thrown open as best I can. Sometimes it requires lots of grease in the hinges and other times I enlist the aid of an occasional crowbar and wedge. One thing that’s always required is a watchful eye. Otherwise, those doors slam shut and wind up needing a lot more muscle to coax them open again.</p>
<p>If we&#8217;ve packed it in on love—and I&#8217;m talking about love of life, of self, of others, of younameit— if we entertain the lie that our one and only ship has sailed, that it&#8217;s just as well, because we get seasick or, we&#8217;re not destined to ever be happy at anything all because there&#8217;s not enough and life is hard and so on—the doors to the heart will seal up with an unconscious gunk so thick, the sound and texture of truly loving connections get harder and harder to recognize.</p>
<p>Funny, isn’t it, that we say so easily and so often that we want this and that from our relationships, but, if our hearts are gummed up and bolted over on lockdown, we may as well be professing that stuff from behind bullet-proof glass in a hi-crime, late-night drive-thru because that’s how attractive you’re looking to Love. By the way, if you’ve never had the pleasure of ordering from one of those places, take my word for it: it’s dangerous, the food sucks and feels awful going down.</p>
<p>Because I can, I’ve drummed up a short list of 5 sure ways to know when and if you’re approaching the dangerous state of Love or Life on lockdown. Again, this is includes but is not limited to romantic love. I’ve left a lot off of this list, so feel free to send me your own personal favorites if you want, as I’d like to read &#8216;em.</p>
<p><strong>1. I&#8217;m too old for love. </strong>Once I officially entered the realm of what some would call middle age, which, last time I checked was 35, I quickly found that notion of being too old for anything that’s true and good, was bogus. I don’t know about you, but I fully intend to give and receive great loving in every area of my life until it’s curtains. And, me being me, I&#8217;ll find a way to keep doing it from the other side, too.</p>
<p><strong>2. There&#8217;s not enough to go around.</strong>In my unsolicited opinion, it doesn’t make sense to use this line of reasoning if you’re looking for a relationship, a hobby, or any other way to get engaged in your life because all you need is one person, one situation, one dream and all of it starts with <em>you</em>. So, unless you live in a town with a population of about six—providing four of whom aren&#8217;t you or related to you if it&#8217;s romance we&#8217;re talking about—then there’s still a chance for connection. Second, I’d ask you to revise that ‘out there’ bit, too. Because, odds are, when you take a moment to really listen to yourself talk in terms of limits, you’ll find that they come from somewhere inside your state of mind.</p>
<p><strong>3. I don’t ‘do’ the dating scene.</strong> So what. Neither do most of the people &#8216;out there&#8217; on the scene themselves. I’ve been to enough speed dating, singles’ dances, social outings, blind dates, and ‘special’ events to know there are plenty people who might have fared better to stay home and work on their presentation before unleashing themselves on the general public. But, they didn’t. And good for them because those people know, like the rest of us could stand to know for ourselves, that you have to at minimum—<em>minimum!</em>—show up to win.</p>
<p><strong> 4. Nobody likes me. </strong>Now you&#8217;re getting dramatic and, forgive me, but I&#8217;ve mislaid my violin. As one who’s all about healthy drama in appropriate quantities, I can tell you this one will get you nowhere fast. In fact, there are so many problems with this line of thought that I can’t even begin to address it. And furthermore, you’re starting to rile me up by virtue of the fact that you’re trying to make me convince you you’re likable in the first place. Know what? With that <em>nobody likes me </em>whiny attitude, maybe you’re right!</p>
<p><strong>5. I don&#8217;t want to be hurt again. </strong>Let me ask you this: Why stay locked in a bomb shelter eating Spam when you can live above ground dining on fancy organics any time your want? Keeping yourself hidden away from life, safely removed from the threat of any possible attack or upset from your canned routine winds up being a form of torture all its own, don&#8217;t you think? Now get yourself out there! Or not. I’ve learned my lesson and I’ve given up trying to tell people what to do. More or less.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - -</p>
