		<title>Passages</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/gsxFrls6zHY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/08/30/passages/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 31 Aug 2011 05:00:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1565</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Social networking is deep. For lots of reasons. But, today, I happen to think it&#8217;s particularly intense because it&#8217;s got me thinking about how it is that I can share a laugh, swap stories, discuss the issues, mingle, chat and seem totally engaging and current from anywhere—even the bathroom. And that I can do so [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/trailblazing.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1569" title="trailblazing" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/trailblazing-300x224.jpg" alt="" width="355" height="265" /></a></p>
<p>Social networking is deep. For lots of reasons. But, today, I happen to think it&#8217;s particularly intense because it&#8217;s got me thinking about how it is that I can share a laugh, swap stories, discuss the issues, mingle, chat and seem totally engaging and current from anywhere—even the bathroom. And that I can do so with anyone from anyplace in the world totally blows my mind. From Colorado to Cairo if I want. Boulder to Bangladesh too—all without ever having to shower, shake hands, open my mouth or leave the comfort of my living room. Talk about friendship with benefits!</p>
<p><span id="more-1565"></span></p>
<p>Never before has so little been required to have so much. Hundreds of friends—thousands if I push it—at the click of a button. And they all like me; to them, I&#8217;m neat and happening. Savvy and smart. Me—they all think awesome. Until they don&#8217;t. Which brings me to the <em>un</em>benefits of friendship. My aunt used to tell us young drivers we had to &#8220;stick your nose out there&#8221; if we ever expected to merge into fast-moving traffic. She was hardly a passive shotgun rider, but she was right about that. And the same goes for navigating traffic on the Internet superhighway: if I want to get anywhere, I must jut my nose, toes—and neck, it appears—out there by letting folks all over the so-called social sites know I&#8217;m ready to take my chances in the fast lane.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s all harmless enough at first, this act of getting out there. Last year I wrote a post about how I had pretty much resigned myself to thinking it might be enough, maybe, to write quietly in the margins of my life, to eek out a few pieces every now and again in hopes of persuading some publisher or generous real-life friend who owed me one to be so kind as to read my material. But I quickly gave up on that resignation because the thing about being a writer is that writers need readers. Which means we, I, by way of my work, have to be out there—nose, toes, head, neck and all. No two ways about it, it can&#8217;t be helped, this chronic writing condition. Sometimes, I liken it to psychosis.</p>
<p>The American essayist and scholar H.L. Mencken once said the writer was that person &#8220;in whom the normal vanity of all men is so vastly exaggerated that he finds it a sheer impossibility to hold it in. His overpowering impulse is to gyrate before his fellow men, flapping his wings and emitting defiant yells. This being forbidden by the police of all civilized countries, he takes it out by putting his yells on paper.&#8221;</p>
<p>A story: Within twenty-four hours of edging my nose into online traffic, which means creating a highly visible Honey Help YourSelf page on Facebook, I got quickly friended <em>and</em> unfriended by someone who didn&#8217;t care for what I was doing. If I read this another way, I&#8217;d say the outright rejection of my work felt like this person was not only calling my baby, my brand new labor of love, <em>un</em>lovable, <em>un</em>impressive and, horror of horrors, <em>un</em>friendable. When I learned of the loss, my mind went straight to the possible reasons why I&#8217;d been unliked. I wanted to message that person and let him or her know I really didn&#8217;t suck as a human being, that I truly didn&#8217;t mean to piss them off and that contrary to whatever it was they thought about me and my writing baby, I am generally not an irreverent upstart.</p>
<p>After deciding it would be pointless to find the offended or offending unfriender, as it were, I considered why I&#8217;d been so concerned about that one person&#8217;s response, rather than appreciating the support I&#8217;d received. When I take this exploration deeper and look at why the urge for approval from strangers, I can&#8217;t help but travel back to the kid in me who equated praise with acceptance, stability—however temporary—and an all-is-well feeling in the world. To that girl in me, whenever people left me without a proper explanation, it meant I probably had a hand in it or that I was somehow responsible for their departure. And, surprisingly, that feeling in me lit up like a string of Christmas lights when someone I hardly knew &#8220;left me&#8221; hanging by the side of the web.</p>
<p>Frankly, sometimes people just won&#8217;t like us—won&#8217;t like <em>me</em>, my writing, my opinions, or even my recent choice of hair color. And that&#8217;s okay. They&#8217;re not <em>wrong</em>. Do I need to call those people out as losers for not acknowledging my sparkling qualities and irrepressible need to flap my writing wings up and down the Internet highway? Absolutely&#8230;not.</p>
<p>I was reminded that every relationship has its own cycles and that, within those, each person has his or her own rules of engagement and freedom of choice that don&#8217;t always compliment the other person&#8217;s. That&#8217;s the nature of real relating and friendship, I think: we have to make room for each other and our stuff. Especially when we&#8217;re feeling sensitive in new and uncharted territory.</p>
<p>It takes courage to step into a brand new direction. And I can tell you already, when you begin to blaze new trails for yourself, you&#8217;d better expect things to heat up. There will be fire, much of it originating from under your own butt. When you blaze a trail, you may find that you&#8217;ll have to run that sucker right through the heart of town, laying waste to the old outposts of your fear and blasting past those zones of comfort. No doubt you&#8217;ll scare the children and babies, but they&#8217;ll be okay, taking courage from your lead as you gut it out and blow the roof off of business as usual. Count on it all.</p>
<p>- – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; – &#8211; -</p>
<p>For the extended audio version of this entry, which, I caution you, also happens to contain a bit of base language, click on my Honeycast player above. Or find it in iTunes.</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
