		<item>
		<title>Popcorn Kills!</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/2UGe0s5-3OU/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/08/01/popcorn-kills/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 01 Aug 2011 18:53:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1523</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Have you heard about the latest menace on the streets, popcorn brain? No, I&#8217;m not hurling an insult at you, so calm down. I&#8217;m telling you about a very real threat to our overall mental health and wellness: popcorn brain. A group Chinese researchers did a big study recently and found that people who spend lots of [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Popcorn.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1525" title="Popcorn" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Popcorn-300x241.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="322" /></a></p>
<p>Have you heard about the latest menace on the streets, popcorn brain? No, I&#8217;m not hurling an insult at you, so calm down. I&#8217;m telling you about a very real threat to our overall mental health and wellness: popcorn brain. A group Chinese researchers did a big study recently and found that people who spend lots of time shopping, tweeting, texting, and IMing on their electronic devices have less gray matter, or brain power, to apply to critical thinking compared to folks who live holes and have no connection to computers, cell phones, e-readers, TVs, radios, appliances and anything else powered by an on/off button. Those researchers dubbed this electronic obsession as Internet Attention Deficiency. I think. And don&#8217;t ask me who officially dubbed this thing popcorn brain either. I can&#8217;t be sure because I wasn&#8217;t on the site long enough to actually retain what they said.</p>
<p><span id="more-1523"></span></p>
<p>I skipped down to the boldface hyperlink inviting me to take an online test on another website so I could determine whether I was indeed afflicted with this new disorder. Before I could get to that page, though, I remembered I&#8217;d been researching a topic for an article I&#8217;d been thinking about, which was the main reason I got online in the first place —after checking my Netflix queue, that is. That article, the one I was supposed to be researching, came up conveniently, at the precisely right time, as much of my inspiration does: right when I was busy doing other things.</p>
<p>In this case of &#8216;doing other things,&#8217; I&#8217;d been putting in some real work on the book I&#8217;ve been whining about doing for the last decade, or seven years, at least.  Remember? You know, it was one of those goals on my resolutions list way back in January. Speaking of goals, resolutions and January, shall I give you a moment to go back and consider your own priorities right now before you get all caught up in judging me and my tedious back-and-forth on my novel project, thank you very much? Seriously, I&#8217;ll wait. My Attention-Deficited popcorn brain could probably use the break anyway.</p>
<p>Right. Break. Did somebody just say <em>Take yourself a break, </em>honey? Done!</p>
<p>The way I see it, a break means getting out if I&#8217;ve been inside, or going in if I&#8217;ve been outside too long (because you never want to be the <em>last </em>one to leave the party, FYI). So, to give myself time away from the things I wasn&#8217;t doing, and from the latest shocking discoveries in the field of gray matter and brain science, I decided to take myself to hear some live music venue and order myself a rum and Coke—heavy on the ice—while I pondered my book and the new article I&#8217;m going to get to as soon as I do my research. Right after I finish this entry and recall that piece of the dream I had that was alerting me to&#8230; to&#8230; Oh, the accursed popcorn.</p>
<p>Not long into my outing, I grab a seat at the bar and drift into creating an imaginary list of things I need to get to, itemizing them into two columns of need vs. want, then fun vs. boring, then yes vs. no, and finally into no particular order at all, except maybe A vs. B or left vs. right. While unconsciously engaged in this process, I stop to catch my reflection in the bar room mirror when I realize my head was darting back and forth like I was a spectator engrossed in an invisible ping pong match. Catching myself like that, looking back out at myself from behind the bar and bottom shelf booze, the reflection was, to say the least, not flattering. <em>Gee, I&#8217;m hardly looking relaxed during this inspired break</em>, I thought. <em>In fact, I seem completely panicked and I&#8217;ve got that look of a trapped cat in a rainstorm.</em></p>
<p>It&#8217;s these kinds of comparisons, comparisons that contain more truth than fiction, that make me fear an even worse-case scenario: that there in the bar, where I went for an escape and undeserved break from the rigors of worrying about popcorn brain (undiagnosed), my book (unwritten), my article (unrealized), and honeycast (ha!), I come to the blatant conclusion in that moment that <em>I am one stinking hot mess</em>.</p>
<p>To the casual observer, my darting glances and look of puzzlement might have indicated I&#8217;ve got Social Anxiety Disorder. Or Seasonal Allergy and Disease. Either way, it is not cute what I&#8217;m seeing in myself. Not at all. It&#8217;s just SAD, really.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s epiphanies like these that make me think bad things about fun-time food and refreshments like popcorn and fizzy sweet drinks created with the express purpose of taking the edge off. They make me think all of the work I&#8217;m not getting done and that time is ticking—and that, if I truly am at the midpoint of this life journey of mine—then, oh crap. And worse: I&#8217;ve probably got MAD, too (The Midlife Apathy Deal)!</p>
<p>Sometimes, this is life.</p>
<p>And so is this: After pondering my hot mess self on the barstool, held captive by my SAD, MAD decreased-capacity popcorn thinking, I grabbed a cocktail napkin and began to write. It didn&#8217;t take long before I started laughing myself back toward a clearing away from the overgrowth my wild imagination. Once there, I was able to move into productivity mode more quickly than I would have if I&#8217;d tried to merely will my way through the madness by pretending that, U<em>m, no that rattling sound you hear is definitely </em>not <em>coming from that loose screw between my ears</em>.</p>
<p>And that&#8217;s where knowing oneself and having faith enter in. If I didn&#8217;t know what I do about myself and the way I think and work, it would have been way too easy to stay mired in a pit of crippling messages from the media and consequent self-diagnoses. If I didn&#8217;t trust my own process of making friends with my emotions and all of the mental driftwood that floats up as a result of experiencing my feelings, I might have dropped those notions of writing, reading, recording and doing the work required to get me where I wanted to be. Had I tried to ignore my restlessness and frustration or force myself to act like everything was fine when that wasn&#8217;t entirely the case, I might have wound up doing more harm than good.</p>
<p>I could have simply explained away my monkey mind as it swooped in and swung me from fear to panic and back again without my permission. Had I not known what my own creative process sometimes feels like, I might have succumbed to the peanut gallery&#8217;s voices of insult, injury and doubt and never forged ahead with my ideas. Looking back, I might have never written the first word on this website. I could have feasted on the peanuts and popcorn junk food regimen of self-limitation. It would have been a no-brainer to beat back those dreams in me as the ramblings of a MAD SAD popcorn-brained crazy person. But I chose to ride the roller coaster of emotion wherever it carried me. <em>Well</em>, as CeeLo Green asks, <em>Does that make me crazaay? Does that make me crazaay?</em> Possibly. But, you know what? <em>We&#8217;re never gonna survive </em>– and get to living the lives we really want – <em>unless we get a little crazy</em>. Seal said some of that last piece; I can&#8217;t take all of the credit.</p>
<p>Having faith in the part of you that is always holding steady on the inside can change the game in ways we couldn&#8217;t anticipate on our best day. Some might call that all-knowing part of us the Inner Voice, the Higher Self, God, Buddha, Universe, Big Cheese or whatever. Maybe it doesn&#8217;t even matter what you call it, or that you call it anything. But the point is, if we want to change the game, we&#8217;ve got to get into it. Then we&#8217;ve got to be willing to play it out. I&#8217;ll quit the sports analogy now, but you get my point. I hope.</p>
<p>Moving through to the other side of my mini-drama helped to shift me somehow for the better, and I can tell you first-hand that the view from here is awesome. Distractionless, even. Feel free to join me, won&#8217;t you? You&#8217;ll find me in the clearing, just beyond the overgrowth. It&#8217;s not that far, so no need for extra baggage. Maybe you&#8217;ll want to carry water and snacks as you make your way. But, please, leave your popcorn—and peanuts—behind.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~4/2UGe0s5-3OU" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
