		<item>
		<title>Nuts ‘n’ Honey</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/etsKZSfMrVo/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/06/19/nuts-n-honey/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 19 Jun 2011 06:24:43 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1437</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[It&#8217;s been a week—a rickety emotional ride for every frigging minute of the 168 hours that comprised the last seven days. More or less. Well, if you want to break it down, I suppose you could take away the 56 hours I slept and the 40 I frittered away at work, which account for a [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/NutsNHoney.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2178" title="Supermarket" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/NutsNHoney.jpg" alt="" width="435" height="276" /></a></p>
<p>It&#8217;s been a week—a rickety emotional ride for every frigging minute of the 168 hours that comprised the last seven days. More or less. Well, if you want to break it down, I suppose you could take away the 56 hours I slept and the 40 I frittered away at work, which account for a different realm of headache than the issues I&#8217;m addressing here. Then we&#8217;ve got the time with friends, perhaps some of which was allotted to discussing the issues I&#8217;m about to lay out for you, but, for the most part, the time I took enjoying my friends isn&#8217;t the focus of this post, so yeah, let&#8217;s subtract 15 more from our running total.</p>
<p><span id="more-1437"></span></p>
<p>By now, my 168 hours of angst and upset is looking more like 57, but since I&#8217;m on a kick, I&#8217;ve got to go one better and tell you I burned lots of hours on the basics, too—maintaining my general upkeep and securing food, clothing and shelter type stuff—in addition to meditation and true minutia like texting, cyber jiving and thumb twiddling that I won&#8217;t bother to detail here. So the final tally for time in hours spent pissed off and emotionally locked in the jaws of this week&#8217;s beast was more like 6. I&#8217;m happy to report that I&#8217;ve got some perspective now, so I can see more objectively into these events, which couldn&#8217;t have been any more divinely timed—or absurd. And I assure you, it didn&#8217;t feel so &#8220;divine&#8221; being on the receiving end at the time.</p>
<p>Still, upset is upset—whether it&#8217;s 6 seconds or 6 hours. Granted, we all have those moments that challenge our good natures and make us want to call it all off, go fetal, pull the blankie up around our ears and not come out of our darkened rooms in the victim &#8216;hood until further notice. Believe me, I get it.</p>
<p>Let&#8217;s take my week of outrage as an example—okay, my 360 minutes of anger. On Sunday I had a phone reading with a lovely client who was referred to me by a dear friend we had in common. At the end of our session, the client and I had begun to chat about our wonderful mutual friend and during our exchange it turned out that this client and I had been to several of the same social events without ever having met officially at the time.</p>
<p>The client and I went on to talk about how much fun we&#8217;d had at one particular party when the client added how funny it was to see <em>that one van full of black people driving around in the dirt parking lot.</em></p>
<p><em>Hmm,</em> I thought. <em>What do we have here? </em>I asked myself. <em>Nothing,</em> I decided.</p>
<p>Very shortly thereafter we said our polite goodbyes and ended the call. As I considered the client&#8217;s comment, almost immediately my mind raced back to earlier that morning in the hardware store when, after finally having found the perfect terra cotta pot for the new plant I&#8217;d just bought, I rounded the corner of the aisle in the direction of the register when I noticed a woman who, not a moment before had been engaged in a lively chat with a man across the aisle roughly 4 feet away. Her eyes meeting mine, she scrambled back over to her shopping cart to secure the zippers and straps on the purse sitting unattended in the top compartment of the shopping cart near the end of the aisle from whence I had emerged.</p>
<p><em>Okay,</em> I thought. <em>Here we are again.</em> I say <em>again</em> because a similar incident happened in the Safeway a few days prior when a woman reaching for a can of beans down the aisle from me noticed my approach and quickly abandoned what she&#8217;d been doing to close the 2-foot chasm between herself, her cart and her precious purse.</p>
<p>Skip to the Saturday night concert I attended with my Kenyan friend Adimu as the two of us are laughing and chatting when a handsome white guy named Steve approached us and spoke of how he&#8217;d noticed us earlier at the bar, but he&#8217;d been <em>too afraid to talk to us because, well,</em> he said, he just didn&#8217;t <em>know</em>.</p>
<p><em>Didn&#8217;t know</em> what? Adimu and I smiled, inquiring in unison.</p>
<p><em>Well,</em> he flushed,<em> you were just standing there talking and you&#8217;re so exotic and beautiful. I just had to say hi.</em></p>
<p>The three of us chatted a bit and as he turned to go, my friend and I thanked him for saying hello. Later, we puzzled at how many more men probably felt similarly at seeing us.</p>
<p>Now let&#8217;s skip to the Memorial Day festival event at held down at the town creek when my friend Kelly and I venture into a stall to fawn over some particularly beautiful wind chimes. No sooner had we entered the stall than the vendor, who was white, tells my friend and I how stunning we are and how much <em>grounding energy</em> we&#8217;ve brought to her booth. So much of it, in fact, that it&#8217;s calmed the winds that had been kicking up all about the festival tents that day. Oh, I should mention here that my friend Kelly is also black.</p>
<p>I purchased a gorgeous wind chime, we smiled politely and said our goodbyes. Later, Kelly and I puzzled over how we might bottle and market our black magic to the masses.</p>
<p>Moving along. The following Saturday night: Adimu and I are standing on the sidewalk talking after having met for dinner. She&#8217;d asked me whether I&#8217;d heard about the latest pseudoscientific study outlining the myriad reasons why black women are the most ugly and fat of any women in the world. That&#8217;s according to a Japanese economist and blogger writing for a respected(?) psychology journal. By that point I was simply up to <strong>here</strong> with the madness and began to say as much when the distinct aroma of cannabis caught our attention.</p>
<p>Just as we recognized the wafting smell of pot in the air, a youngish brunette strolled up and clasped our right hands in hers before we could say a word. Then she began singing <em>don&#8217;t you worry about a thayayang pretty mammas</em> and kissed the backs of our palms, beaming at the both of us, repeatedly professing her undying love for Stevie Wonder and <em>do you love him, too? Don&#8217;t you just?</em> Her eyes twinkled.</p>
<p>Adimu and I smiled politely, nodded and said our goodbyes to the giddy young woman as she blew kisses in our direction, flashed us weak peace signs and strode away on the arm of an equally elated companion.</p>
<p>Like I said, <em>it&#8217;s been a week.</em></p>
<p>So here&#8217;s the thing: It&#8217;s so thoroughly tiresome to encounter people who are living in response to stereotypes, fears and foolishness. Even the occasional fantasy. Because it robs us of the chance to be ourselves and to create relationships from scratch, rather than from behind the eight ball of weird assumptions. Another truth: we all do it. And I like it even less when I see it at play in myself—it&#8217;s doubly exhausting because I <em>know</em> none of us are what we appear to be on the face of it all. In fact, we&#8217;re all of us far greater, infinitely more luminous, and just flat-out way more amazing than we realize. Can I get a witness here, honey? Anybody?</p>
<p>I want to run full-out, banging on drums, howling into the darkness like a loon, kicking up a ruckus, screaming this truth in the streets, but I&#8217;m afraid I might be profiled and surreptitiously disappeared into the Rockies.</p>
<p>Just kidding?</p>
<p>I want to let everybody know it&#8217;s safe and vitally necessary for us to come out from behind the lines, that it&#8217;s okay to drop our guards (not purses!) and really connect, to mingle more easily and simply <em>be</em>. It&#8217;s our duty to do so because it gives other people the permission to follow suit. And once we start taking this stuff seriously, the fact that we really are linked, like it or not, can&#8217;t you just <em>imagine all the people&#8230;</em> (cue John Lennon music). It could change the way we think, the movies that get made, the stuff we buy, the way we live and love.</p>
<p>So, let&#8217;s get started. I&#8217;m totally committed. Welcome one and all! Especially non-people of color! Or is that people of non-color? Okay, so first meeting&#8217;s at my place, Sunday. 2.5 hours max—150 minutes. There will be tofu turkey, potato salad. Maybe even a clown. You in?</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; - -</p>
<p>You might also like:</p>
<p><a title="Community Service" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2012/01/29/community-service/" target="_blank">Community Service</a></p>
