		<item>
		<title>The Numbers</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/AQQ8O0GM9iw/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/06/05/the-numbers/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 06 Jun 2011 02:02:15 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Sweet Talk]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=1412</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[You know that feeling of slowly waking up from a fog of days – weeks, months or more – of time spent navel gazing or gaping in the direction of a horizon you know is your own but doesn&#8217;t feel the least bit familiar? The Horizon: that metaphorical creme-filled moment of finally having arrived, of [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/the-horizon1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1416" title="the horizon" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/the-horizon1-300x200.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="300" /></a></p>
<p>You know that feeling of slowly waking up from a fog of days – weeks, months or more – of time spent navel gazing or gaping in the direction of a horizon you know is your own but doesn&#8217;t feel the least bit familiar?</p>
<p><span id="more-1412"></span></p>
<p>The Horizon: that metaphorical creme-filled moment of finally having arrived, of having at last achieved the elusive thing that would snap your life into place like the sorely needed chiropractic adjustment you never had. This horizon is the hoped for moment when you finally have all the money, time, freedom, courage, sex and love you need to live the life you&#8217;ve always wanted. This mythical place exists as a faraway, would-be parallel life that flickers in the distance, teasing us with the lure of perfect-world conditions tailor made for us if only&#8230;if only.</p>
<p>Recognize that place? Put another way, let&#8217;s say this horizon represents all of those goals you set for yourself by way of daydreaming, wishing, whining or laying down in writing way back in January. Yep – resolutions! – those things loosely hoped for and unmoored enough in our intentions to get pushed so far out to sea that they become practically impossible to bring back into focus or ever feel excited about again.</p>
<p>When our goals get set adrift, it becomes easy to dry up at the thought of traversing the uncertainty of murky waters and all that lies beneath you and the dream.</p>
<p>At the same time, those dull shores of our good intentions and rationalizing feel about as comfortable as the silent but deadly pull of quicksand. So, what to do when you feel yourself frozen and sinking fast in desperation for the unlived life?</p>
<p>For starters, breathe. Not only will doing so help you calm down and keep an unsightly meltdown at bay, but breathing and taking time to really feel the air moving through you is a tremendously simple, simply powerful grounding force that connects you to the moment, and what&#8217;s more present than breathing? It also keeps you tapped in to your own guidance and sends a message to your body that you&#8217;re safe, which helps it reduce the rush of what I call Holy Crap hormones that get deployed by our brains when shit hits the fan.</p>
<p>A &#8220;real world&#8221; scenario looks like this: On Monday, May 23rd, I awoke under a cloud of dread. For all intents and purposes, it was my own personal D Day. D as in discussion. D as in big decisions. D as in dammit. My D Day meant I had to meet with Greg, the financial planner. The only other day I dreaded as much or more than that came roughly 6 months ago, when I met with him for the first time this year.</p>
<p>Greg and I spent the morning – which to outside eyes looked more like fifty minutes – talking about money. My money. More like <em>he</em> spent the time talking about it while I attempted to listen, glassy-eyed in his direction as he assessed my situation, suggesting areas for improvement and proactive strategies that would keep me from being relegated to a cat-food diet in my twilight years. As he walked me toward the door I felt the clenching in my chest began to loosen as I slowly returned to normal breathing.</p>
<p>On the way home I wondered whether anyone else had ever felt as utterly frustrated and perplexed as I had in that moment. Sure, I&#8217;d heard accounts of people whose lives had been irrevocably wrecked by corporate greed and the likes of Enron as well as those who&#8217;d been mislead by woefully misguided Madoffs the world over. I also knew about recent catastrophic events on Wall Street and the current numbers that painted a far from pretty picture of the world&#8217;s economy. So, no, I knew intellectually that I was hardly alone in my concern about the financial future. I also knew that because I had the luxury of having resources enough to engage the help of a professional said volumes in and of itself.</p>
<p>Still, this was <em>me</em> we&#8217;re talking about, and that made it different somehow. Or so I told myself. More to the point, after our exchange I saw very clearly that I&#8217;d been picking at the bones of a leftover message that said I wasn&#8217;t good with money, and was in some way undeserving, destined to live from hand to mouth if I was lucky, despite the The Numbers that unequivocally said otherwise. That&#8217;s when I knew it was time to reach for help.</p>
<p>After our extended projections about how I could make my dollars stretch, climb, reach and expand across the void and swim upstream against a down current and then emerge from troubled waters to fly skyward, with an eye toward feathering my nest for the day when I was an old bird and would need it most – frankly, it was all too much. And I&#8217;d been way too emotional about the whole thing.</p>
<p>Because I&#8217;m the <em>creative</em> one, I fed on the message given to me that said artists starve and because they do, they&#8217;re rarely savvy in business, nevermind what their Numbers say. In my head, number-crunching projectionists were aliens who spoke above my head in indecipherable percentage points and economic jargon that ranked lower even than the last item on my list of priorities. And my visit with Greg brought all of those old ghosts racing back to strike at the tender wounded artist heart of me. The room spun, my head throbbed and all I knew was I needed a cookie – fast!</p>
<p>The reason I chose this scenario was was not to admit how close I&#8217;d come to throwing my hands up in Jesus-take-the-wheel desperation at the mere suggestion of how I could make my money work harder for me. I use this example to illustrate yet again how vitally important it is to be in the moment and how equally necessary it is to enlist the help of a trained professional to provide us with a game plan when we can&#8217;t muster up an effective one of our own.</p>
<p>To my first point – and perhaps you&#8217;ll see how this example could apply to any number of your own blind spots and power struggles – because I woke up that morning with the <em>expectation</em> of dread and impending powerlessness, I had thrown myself completely out of the present and had yielded my power to the old fear-based lie of being a starving artist, destined to a paltry subsistence of cat food, cardboard boxes, and back alley gutters. All before my feet hit the floor. Honey, help!</p>
<p>What&#8217;s worse is that when I showed up, half-present to our meeting, I glazed over, looking for cover from a deadly ambush of The Numbers. So, I occupied myself by wondering about the antiquated flip phone I noticed sitting atop a mound of folders on Greg&#8217;s desk. I imagined that when people called him, their conversations were punctuated by the crackling background LP sound each time he said his piece.</p>
<p>But speaking of help, that&#8217;s the other point: it really is an act of empowerment to engage the assistance of trained professionals who know how to hold the space for us to truly get things done. And there&#8217;s absolutely no shame in that. And another thing: reaching for sweets in a time of perceived crisis is probably not the best means to achieving long-term results other than diabetes and weight gain.</p>
<p>For lots of years I&#8217;d said I wanted, needed, to organize my financial life in a way that I hadn&#8217;t felt confident enough to do on my own. So this year I flipped the script and actually did something I was good at in service to my goal: I made a list of objectives and browsed the web with them in mind. I placed some calls and booked informational appointments with advisors I felt I&#8217;d click with. And <em>voilà</em>, introducing Greg. I&#8217;m happy to say he&#8217;s fast become the ally I had in mind: a pro who wouldn&#8217;t flinch and bail when the markets tanked and interest rates rocketed. A formidable visionary whose passion and experience would help me stay the course and finish stronger than I might have, left to my on devices &#8230; and, until now, excuses.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;ve ever found it hard to ask for help in service to something you wanted to do, something that&#8217;s been in rotation on your own goals list for years, and especially if you&#8217;ve ever knocked yourself for not being able to <em>just do it</em> on your own, then you&#8217;ve probably experienced the dizziness getting stuck in this kind of irrational roundabout.</p>
<p>The truth is is that help is available when you make your needs known and reach out for it. Sometimes it&#8217;s just a matter of risking the truth of what&#8217;s eating you. Believe it or not, getting real about what&#8217;s been holding you back can act as the wind in your sails, setting you back on a direct course toward your dreams.</p>
<p>To me getting real – meaning getting outside of my own head and those old notions – enables me to breathe fully <em>into</em> the moment and <em>out</em> of the drama a lot more easily. Only then can I clear the way for real work to begin. Again.</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
