		<item>
		<title>Reflections</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/_s5-4h1XfC4/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/02/11/reflections/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 11 Feb 2011 08:44:50 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Good Energy]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=999</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Objects in your rearview mirror may appear closer than they seem. As far as today&#8217;s entry goes, truer words were never spoken-or in this case, poorly paraphrased. Looking at this image always takes me back to a reading I did once. As usual, the client was lovely, and the experience was illuminating for us both. [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/reflections.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1000" title="reflections" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/reflections.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="300" /></a></p>
<p>Objects in your rearview mirror may appear closer than they seem. As far as today&#8217;s entry goes, truer words were never spoken-or in this case, poorly paraphrased. Looking at this image always takes me back to a reading I did once. As usual, the client was lovely, and the experience was illuminating for us both. At one point during our session, I saw the client in his car on an open road, his hands solidly grasping the wheel at ten and two. The quiet tree-lined street was lit by nothing more than a late afternoon sun. The picture was resplendent and warm – a very good sign as far as I was concerned. And yet, it felt &#8216;off.&#8217; For one thing, although my client was facing forward, his attention was focused behind him – in his rearview mirror – instead of out at the road and what lie ahead. And two, he wasn&#8217;t moving.</p>
<p><span id="more-999"></span></p>
<p>I use that snippet (with permission, of course) to illustrate not only the importance of separating ourselves out from the past in order to move ahead in life, but also to remind you that, if we know how to view them, mirrors to the past can be a great way to gauge our own progress. Neat, huh? Honey, who knew.</p>
<p>&#8216;Kay, so why this message now? you ask. Well, because it&#8217;s February, and February is the what-the-effingest month of short memory, of coming up short, of low motivation, of apathy, idling and neglect. And I&#8217;ll speak for myself here, but in the past two weeks alone, I&#8217;ve watched myself not only bungle, fumble and drop the metaphorical ball of my goals more times than I&#8217;ll ever let you in on. And how could I? After my last post — I mean, come on — I was all charged up and <em>gung ho</em> on my goals and everything was clicking and singing along just fine. But a hiccup arrived as Late January tugged at the edges of my magic carpet. Before I knew it, my <em>gung</em> was gone and all I had left was one tired <em>ho</em> that couldn&#8217;t be bothered to keep it up any longer, so to speak. Besides y&#8217;all, I&#8217;m the self-helping motivational one. I&#8217;m supposed to have all this stuff sewn up and at least be able to stay on track for a good ten days without buckling, right? Durrrr&#8230;</p>
<p>So: mirrors. Armchair Psych tells us mirroring occurs when a person&#8217;s actions are reflective of our own. For example, say you&#8217;re having a conversation with person A when A, who happens to like and respect you, starts unconsciously parroting your body language. Positive mirroring means A is engaged in what you&#8217;re saying and genuinely admires you and that&#8217;s a good thing. Unless, however, A is hip to this psych thing and is trying to manipulate you toward their own agendas, which then makes A an A-<em>hole</em>. Another form of mirroring occurs when people display behaviors we may recognize as our own, but are reflective of our past. This happens to us all the time in some form or another, and it can be a real game changer when we&#8217;re able to set our awareness on it. In my own recent experience I was relieved to find those mirrors of the past weren&#8217;t actually driving my life in the present. <em>Hot damn</em>, I thought, <em>shift really</em> does <em>happen!</em></p>
<p>A little story about one of several recent rearview mirroring incidents: I was in a bar — and, no, you don&#8217;t get to judge me for having meaningful life events in bars. Live a little! Anyway, we&#8217;re in this bar when my friend Matt tells me someone asked to buy a product from his brand new business. <em>Can you believe it?</em></p>
<p>Once Matt asked me that, I got triggered and all my alarms went off in that moment. But it&#8217;s not because I&#8217;m a nasty drunk. I got triggered because, in case you didn&#8217;t already know it, I am freakishly serious when it comes to encouraging people in the direction of their dreams and toward the pull of the impossible. I mean, how can I not be? You think anybody struck up a parade for me when I announced I was going to do readings for complete strangers over the phone and get all up in their personal energy business and help them break down their blocks for a modest fee? You think I didn&#8217;t think twice about the glut of <em>bona fide</em> phonies who make my work seem that much more ridiculous – before deciding to go down this road? You think my loved ones hooted and hollered in jubilation when I <em>declared dead people aren&#8217;t really &#8216;dead&#8217; </em>and<em> we&#8217;re part of a Source that we&#8217;ll all return to one day</em> and that studying dreams and Jungian symbology was fast becoming a passion of mine? Yeah &#8230; no. <em><a title="Crickets" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/07/21/crickets/" target="_blank">Crickets</a></em>.</p>
<p>Oh, how easily the fragile embers of inspiration can be extinguished and abandoned at the slightest response, lack of response, perceived lack of response, poorly timed response from others. That&#8217;s part of why I got so pissed (as in angry, not drunk). Here he was, merely trying to be himself and follow the threads of his inspiration, but his fear was closing in without him even recognizing it, and what else could I do but mount up and ride in, my guns drawn against self-doubt and sabotage – the vicious tag team of catastrophe. Even though Matt was trying to enlist my &#8216;support&#8217; for his low-expectation having, confidence-lacking stance, it was the dreaming part of him that really called out to me. It requires a trained ear to listen for the weaving of one&#8217;s threads, and I discuss that in – you guessed it! – <em><a title="Threads" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/05/04/threads/" target="_blank">Threads</a></em>. I invite you to give it a look.</p>
<p>How many times have you had a tender hope or dream that you wanted to bring into the world and mustered up just enough courage to share the idea with someone you trusted and got nothing more than the stinkeye or worse in return? Sadly, repeated replies of non-support and indifference from others can lead us to believe that maybe our hopes are little more than jokes played on us by those in positions much higher than our own. It&#8217;s this kind of thinking that causes us to slam the doors on ourselves before we&#8217;ve even got going. I talk about this in <em><a title="Hold That Door!" href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2011/10/08/hold-that-door-2/" target="_blank">Hold that Door</a></em>. But just because the dream gets dissed by some doesn&#8217;t make it unworthy of your best efforts to make it happen. And it&#8217;s never grounds for berating yourself before you&#8217;ve even begun. Such was the case with Matt. And all of us at various points along the way.</p>
<p>See, like most of us, Matt wasn&#8217;t willing to let himself move forward for his goal for lots of reasons that had accumulated over time. So he wedged himself into an impossible dark corner of insecurity and self-sabotage by acting surprised when a stranger showed up unbidden to openly inquire about his work. Rather than working on ways to stay the course with his project, Matt&#8217;s own self-doubt and ambivalence made him more comfortable laughing the incident off as a fluke yet again. Gotta love those reflections.</p>
<p>Hey, can we all join cyberhands in the spirit of kumbayah for a moment to collectively acknowledge all the times we&#8217;ve acted against ourselves and continue to do it in various ways all the time? Don&#8217;t worry, we won&#8217;t need candles or Coke products for this; this revelation will not be televised.</p>
<p>Rather than choosing to laugh with Matt that day, I looked into the mirror he unwittingly held for me and told him he&#8217;d better <em>never</em> again ask me to co-sabotage anything he truly wanted to do. Ev-er. <em>Of course I can believe in you and your work,</em> I yelled. <em>Why</em> wouldn&#8217;t <em>people want what you&#8217;re selling,</em> I cried. <em>And furthermore,</em> I wailed, <em>who are you</em> not <em>to use your natural born gifts when they can clearly help other people!</em></p>
<p>Speaking of A-holes, suffice it to say I cursed my friend <em>a new one</em> that night. Not because I was tipsy by then, or because I&#8217;d been scrambling to catch up on my own stuff, or even because it was coming up on February, the most short-sighted, bitter-fisted month of the year. I lathered my friend in expletives that night because, sometimes, it&#8217;s just what us ladies do in bars.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~4/_s5-4h1XfC4" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded>
