		<slash:comments>3</slash:comments>

			<itunes:subtitle>No matter how much we pout, scream, whine and barter with the powers that be, sometimes answers just don't come. Sometimes, all we get for our efforts is crickets. - If you've ever lived in a place that goes quiet enough at night to experience the mys...</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>No matter how much we pout, scream, whine and barter with the powers that be, sometimes answers just don't come. Sometimes, all we get for our efforts is crickets.

If you've ever lived in a place that goes quiet enough at night to experience the mysterious music of crickets, you'd likely understand why their nocturnal singing is synonymous with the 'out-there' feeling that shows up when you're waiting on laughs at weak jokes or answers—especially if they're spiritual in nature.



For the past month or more I've been wondering at my own guidance. I've also been pouting, screaming, and whining at the void, if you must know. What should I write about? Where am I going with all this stuff, anyway? Where'd my inspiration run off to? How can I tone up my inner thighs? Nothing serious, really, just more existential pondering and navel gazing in hopes of finding my place in what it all means. Again. And I can tell you right now that, for all of my insistent pleas (please, oh please!) to the Higher Power, the answers that came surprised and confounded me in their simplicity and complexity. Without realizing it, I'd been bumbling around the gentle refrain that had been singing to me all along. All I had to do was slow down long enough to listen...to crickets.

But the crickets. When I hear them at night—which usually means it's during that forced stillness just before sleep—I'm amazed at how many of them there are 'out there.' Just chirping away in the dark, their chorus can rage on to the point of distraction, rising and falling in waves like the movements of a symphony. And depending on the day, either I'm all about the majesty of their night music, or I'm annoyed at how completely their persistent humming works my very last nerve.

That's the way my answers have—or seemingly have not—been showing up lately, too. I'm either awed by the grace that reveals itself in mundane places or I'm pissed that I can't make head nor tails of what might be guidance dangling like a juicy fruit just beyond my reach. And when I'm in that latter scenario—unable to grasp the guideposts all around me when I've asked for them—I get all drifty and sideswiped by that unproductive 'out there' feeling. That's when I throw my hands up to the heavens and ask, What gives? Still, crickets.

Naturally, I've got a handful of theories/stories behind this recent cricket phenomena of mine. I'll spare you the whole list, but here are a few to chew on.

1. WE'RE THE CRICKETS. What if every time any one of us sent up a prayer, wish, or thought, it joined the throngs of other people's pleas to form a chaotic chorus of inscrutably beautiful noise offered up to the heavens? And what if that inscrutable noise was in and of itself a collective cry to the Higher Power? Which then might suggest how incredibly and intricately connected we are—right down to our private thoughts. So, if I ask the Higher Power for something, what if that means everybody else in the world is linked to that request too (not to mention their being impacted by the actions I take)? So, the admonition to be careful what we ask for takes on new meaning.

2. ANSWERS ARE CRICKETS. How about this one? What if the answers to our prayers, wishes, dreams and aspirations were as available to us as the constant thrumming of crickets? It's that kind of hidden-in-plain-sight principle that makes us smack at our foreheads and rend garments when we realize how hard we were making things for ourselves when answers and guidance are simply everywhere we turn. It also means we may need to pay closer attention to our general surroundings if we really want to hear what's coming through courtesy of the Higher Power.

3. CRICKETS ON A PLANE. In much the same way Sam Jackson alerted his unfortunate fellow travelers to news they simply couldn't avoid, I too have come to share the inevitable truth of snakes on the plane, honey! Only, I'm announcing crickets in the grass.</itunes:summary>
		<itunes:author>Kriste Peoples</itunes:author>
		<itunes:explicit>no</itunes:explicit>
		<itunes:duration>12:29</itunes:duration>
	<media:content url="http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~5/p7mbpDJopi4/Honey16_Crickets090811.mp3" fileSize="14972993" type="audio/mpeg" /><itunes:keywords>positive,energy,energy,healing,personal,essay,affirmations,clairvoyant,readings,meditation,change,soul,coaching,African,American,woman,psychic,readings,spirituality,women,intuition,intuitive,humor,life,coach</itunes:keywords><feedburner:origLink>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/07/21/crickets/</feedburner:origLink><enclosure url="http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~5/p7mbpDJopi4/Honey16_Crickets090811.mp3" length="14972993" type="audio/mpeg" /><feedburner:origEnclosureLink>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/honeycast/Honey16_Crickets090811.mp3</feedburner:origEnclosureLink></item>
		<item>
		<title>Ruts</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/honeyhelpyourself/~3/w3WddY88gNs/</link>
		<comments>http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/2010/05/30/in-a-rut/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 31 May 2010 01:10:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>honeyhelpyourself@gmail.com (Kriste Peoples)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Good Energy]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/?p=462</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[No two ways about it, ruts suck. Whether physical, mental, spiritual, categorical or slightly implied, sometimes you just can’t win against the sleeping, creeping threat of otherwise harmless ruts appearing along your path every now and again. Okay, maybe not you per se, but I know I can’t always avoid the pits. There’s nothing like [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/DSCN7129-bike-in-bigger-rut-close_800x6001.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-463" src="http://www.honeyhelpyourself.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/DSCN7129-bike-in-bigger-rut-close_800x6001-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>No two ways about it, ruts suck. Whether physical, mental, spiritual, categorical or slightly implied, sometimes you just can’t win against the sleeping, creeping threat of otherwise harmless ruts appearing along your path every now and again. Okay, maybe not <em>you</em> per se, but I know I can’t always avoid the pits.</p>
<p><span id="more-462"></span></p>
<p>There’s nothing like getting stuck in a rut to hinder creative momentum. Picture this: there you are, rolling along just fine, peacefully coasting through an idyllic countryside when you notice you’ve inadvertently steered yourself into an emotional, metaphorical or literal ditch of sorts. Stuck, confounded, powerless, you flail for awhile and throw up your hands wondering where you went wrong—and how to right yourself. If this has never been your experience, then bully for you. Put another way, dear reader, you’re lying and I don’t believe you one bit.</p>
<p>If, however, you know that sinking feeling of stuckness, and often wonder at how to free yourself, then read on because I’ve culled some info that might just help dislodge you and get on with it again.</p>
<p>Here’s what a popular bicycle website has to say on the issue of landing in a rut:</p>
<blockquote><p>“The most common mistake is panicking and trying to steer out of a rut as soon as you get into it. When you do this, your front wheel often can’t “climb” the wall of the rut. Your body leans out while your bike stays stuck-and you crash.”</p></blockquote>
<p>Doesn’t that just beat all?</p>
<p>In case you’re not feeling the enormity of this allusion like I am, here’s the thing: when you find yourself in a slump or rut—a well-worn crevice, pit, or unhealthy habit of any kind, don’t worry about trying to solve it immediately. Sometimes it’s a better use of your energy to simply acknowledge it, period. That’s right, staying put might be just the thing you need for the moment.</p>
<p>To the point about “leaning out,” I totally agree. In energy language, this means being out of alignment within yourself. For example, if your body wants to do something other than what your mind and spirit have in mind, then it’s not long before something gives way and you topple over because of the imbalance. Plenty of folks are riding around like that right now, know. They&#8217;re lopsided and bent out of shape, incongruent—despite their best efforts to prop themselves up. So, for starters, slow down and assess where you are for a minute. It beats panicking, stressing out or otherwise fighting against yourself.</p>
<p>Bicycling.com goes on to say:</p>
<blockquote><p>…make sure you’re in control and not going so slowly that you lack momentum and balance. Look for a spot within the next 10 feet where the walls get shallow, slope upward like a ramp or are uniformly steep (as opposed to jagged and crumbly). Those are the only places from which to steer out.</p></blockquote>
<p>Ha! Now we’re cookin’.</p>
<p>See how important the balancing act is? They don’t tell us to stay in the rut/ditch indefinitely or to fill out a change of address form to the tricky location we’ve landed in. Instead, they say <em>Collect yourself, get a grip, and look ahead for an opening that will point you to higher ground again.</em> In symbolic talk, this means it’s our intention that makes all the difference. See, intention isn’t about where we <em>are</em>, it’s more about where we <em>plan</em> to be. Far stronger than hope, and somewhere in the neighborhood of faith, intention is about us knowing things are seldom as they appear and then pointing ourselves in the direction of our chosen outcome.</p>
<p>No offense to the bicycle pros, but my rut/energy analogy ends where they say there are only a couple of ways to get out. While this might be true in the riding world, energy simply abounds with liberating options if we acknowledge them as such. Good thing you’ve got me handy because I’ve come up with even more rut-releasing, loser-proof tactics of my own that&#8217;ll help you out the next time you get stuck:</p>
<p><strong>1.) CURL UP.</strong> Some folks might call this the Jesus-take-the-wheel approach, but I think this one’s about letting go altogether. Rather than wrestle against inertia and the claustrophobic pinch of ruts, sometimes all you can do is go fetal, surrender to what is and stay under the covers for a little bit. Note: We’re not talking about days and weeks on end. But if that’s what you’re thinking, maybe you <em>do</em> need that change of address form.</p>
<p><strong>2.) CRY OUT.</strong> Ever seen those old Lassie movies where Timmy/Susie falls down the well and cries out for help? Guess what? It worked! By the end of the hour, he/she had the whole town holding candle light vigils, dropping down lifelines to them, making banners and waiting with hot soup and cocoa before the final scene. That said, when you feel yourself hit what you may think is your bottom, don’t just accept the situation as the last word. Make some noise and let people know you&#8217;re down. Holler out from that hole! And here&#8217;s a really big one: let people lend you a hand once they start showing up. Contrary to all the bad news, I happen to know that people actually <em>do</em> want to help. So it&#8217;s up to you to make your needs known.</p>
<p><strong>3.) DON’T FORGET.</strong> Once you’ve curled up, cried out, and consumed all the help people gave you, remember the kindnesses of everyone who stepped in to lift you up. And pay it <em>forward</em>. Don&#8217;t create another rut out of trying to &#8216;pay people back&#8217; in a way that attempts to keep track and settle scores–unless it&#8217;s money you&#8217;ve agreed to repay. Equally important, the next time you feel yourself headed for an inevitable ditch, diversion, or any other type of unproductive rut, keep in mind that it’s only temporary and totally <em>get-out-ofable</em>.</p>
<p><strong>4. ) GO EASY.</strong> If there’s one thing I have a hard time bearing witness to, it’s the way we tend to knock ourselves when things don’t go they way we hoped they would. The next time you find yourself feeling generally bad or lacking in luster, give yourself a break. Think of how you’d ideally like to treat someone else when they’re down. You wouldn’t criticize Timmy and Susie for their unfortunate situation, now would you? (Personally, I blame the parents. But that&#8217;s a whole &#8216;nother story.) And I should hope you treat yourself at least as well as these fictionalized victims. Oh, one more thing: no matter what, you are <em>not</em> a victim. After all, even slumps serve an important purpose in our lives.</p>
<p>By this point, I’m sure you’re already working your way out of your ditch/rut/slump/well and have moved on to bigger challenges. So I’ll stop here for now, signing off and wishing you&#8230;<em>well</em>.</p>
<p>- &#8211; - &#8211; - &#8211; -</p>
